1
00:00:14,014 --> 00:00:17,117
It's already the last month of the year,

2
00:00:17,183 --> 00:00:19,085
-and 2025 is coming to an end.
-Time flies.

3
00:00:19,152 --> 00:00:20,954
Yes, it's already December.

4
00:00:21,021 --> 00:00:22,989
As a year-end special,

5
00:00:23,056 --> 00:00:26,192
we prepared something to decide
the best chef of the season.

6
00:00:26,259 --> 00:00:28,328
The number of stars
are not enough to decide that.

7
00:00:28,395 --> 00:00:29,896
We plan to hold a championship

8
00:00:29,963 --> 00:00:33,033
to decide which one of you
is the best chef of this year.

9
00:00:33,099 --> 00:00:34,567
-Like the Champions League.
-Yes.

10
00:00:34,634 --> 00:00:35,735
Like the baseball postseason.

11
00:00:35,802 --> 00:00:38,405
It's just like how the playoffs
are held for professional baseball.

12
00:00:38,471 --> 00:00:41,341
This episode and the next are
the last two weeks in the regular season.

13
00:00:41,408 --> 00:00:46,413
And there are people who understand
exactly how that works.

14
00:00:46,479 --> 00:00:48,715
Allow me to present the guests.
Come on out!

15
00:00:49,282 --> 00:00:51,284
Today's fridge owners are…

16
00:00:51,684 --> 00:00:52,719
WHOA

17
00:00:52,786 --> 00:00:54,154
…two world-class baseball stars!

18
00:00:55,255 --> 00:00:57,023
…two world-class baseball stars!

19
00:00:57,090 --> 00:00:59,459
Please welcome
Ryu Hyun-jin and Choo Shin-soo!

20
00:00:59,526 --> 00:01:00,727
Come on in!

21
00:01:00,794 --> 00:01:02,062
A PASSIONATE WELCOME

22
00:01:02,128 --> 00:01:03,730
You seem way too happy.

23
00:01:04,631 --> 00:01:07,233
<i>He was the first player</i>
<i>in the history of Korean pro baseball</i>

24
00:01:07,300 --> 00:01:10,503
<i>to win the Rookie of the Year Award</i>
<i>and the MVP Award at the same time.</i>

25
00:01:10,570 --> 00:01:11,805
MOST STRIKEOUTS, MOST WINS

26
00:01:11,871 --> 00:01:15,942
<i>He was also the first Asian player</i>
<i>to record the top ERA.</i>

27
00:01:16,009 --> 00:01:19,345
<i>The living legend of Korean baseball,</i>

28
00:01:19,412 --> 00:01:22,715
Please welcome the Korean Monster,
Ryu Hyun-jin!

29
00:01:23,616 --> 00:01:25,852
Hello, I'm Baseball player Ryu Hyun-jin.

30
00:01:27,987 --> 00:01:29,923
We've always seen you with a cap before,

31
00:01:29,989 --> 00:01:31,791
-but you're stunning today.
-He's good-looking.

32
00:01:31,858 --> 00:01:34,627
-I put a lot of time into this.
-You must have.

33
00:01:35,028 --> 00:01:36,262
ANOTHER ONE WHO PUT TIME INTO IT!

34
00:01:36,329 --> 00:01:37,664
Let me introduce the next guest.

35
00:01:37,730 --> 00:01:39,332
-Sure.
-Goodness.

36
00:01:39,399 --> 00:01:40,934
His cumulative salary

37
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:42,435
amounts to 190 billion won!

38
00:01:42,702 --> 00:01:44,037
HOW MUCH?

39
00:01:44,571 --> 00:01:45,872
THE FIRST ASIAN TO ACHIEVE A CYCLE!

40
00:01:45,939 --> 00:01:47,340
<i>He dominated the MLB,</i>

41
00:01:47,407 --> 00:01:49,943
<i>and in 2022, he led his team</i>
<i>to victory in the Korean Series.</i>

42
00:01:50,009 --> 00:01:52,545
<i>Forever a legend in Korean baseball,</i>

43
00:01:52,612 --> 00:01:55,615
please welcome Choo Choo Train,
Choo Shin-soo!

44
00:01:55,682 --> 00:01:56,883
CHOO CHOO TRAIN, CHOO SHIN-SOO

45
00:01:56,950 --> 00:01:59,886
-Choo Choo Train, Choo Shin-soo!
-Choo Choo Train, Choo Shin-soo!

46
00:01:59,953 --> 00:02:02,388
WHAT A TONGUE TWISTER
CHOO CHOO TRAIN, CHOO SHIN-SOO

47
00:02:02,455 --> 00:02:04,023
Mr. Choo!

48
00:02:04,090 --> 00:02:06,192
He's actually my junior,
but since he's rich, he's the boss.

49
00:02:06,259 --> 00:02:07,160
DOUGH MAKES A BRO A BOSS

50
00:02:07,227 --> 00:02:08,695
-Look at that.
-Look, 190 billion won.

51
00:02:08,761 --> 00:02:10,630
-It's 190 billion won.
-Yes, 190 billion.

52
00:02:10,697 --> 00:02:12,565
It's like winning
<i>Culinary Class Wars</i> 600 times.

53
00:02:13,133 --> 00:02:14,167
Six hundred times?

54
00:02:14,234 --> 00:02:17,470
We heard you enjoy watching
<i>Chef & My Fridge</i>, Shin-soo.

55
00:02:17,537 --> 00:02:19,205
Yes, back when I was in the States,

56
00:02:19,272 --> 00:02:22,208
I'd download the show every week
and watch it.

57
00:02:22,275 --> 00:02:25,979
-I see.
-So I know Chef Hyun-suk quite well.

58
00:02:26,045 --> 00:02:27,780
I don't cook often,

59
00:02:27,847 --> 00:02:30,016
but when I do,
I'd copy your arrogant salt throw.

60
00:02:30,083 --> 00:02:32,719
-I see. You know everything.
-I'd copy him.

61
00:02:32,785 --> 00:02:35,955
After I retired,
I wondered what I should do for fun,

62
00:02:36,022 --> 00:02:40,026
and seriously considered
learning how to cook.

63
00:02:40,093 --> 00:02:41,227
I see.

64
00:02:41,728 --> 00:02:44,664
The baseball season
has ended for Hyun-jin as well…

65
00:02:44,731 --> 00:02:48,201
-Many shows want him to appear.
-…so he must've had many offers.

66
00:02:48,268 --> 00:02:49,936
But he chose to appear only on ours.

67
00:02:51,070 --> 00:02:51,905
As expected.

68
00:02:51,971 --> 00:02:54,040
-And nowhere else.
-Give him a hand.

69
00:02:54,107 --> 00:02:56,910
-That's why he's the GOAT.
-Only our show.

70
00:02:56,976 --> 00:03:00,446
My wife and I enjoyed the show together

71
00:03:00,513 --> 00:03:02,715
since when we were in the States.

72
00:03:02,782 --> 00:03:03,650
THE SHOW TO WATCH IN THE US

73
00:03:03,716 --> 00:03:07,053
So after talking to my wife,
I decided to be here today.

74
00:03:07,120 --> 00:03:08,521
Thanks for coming.

75
00:03:08,588 --> 00:03:12,392
I'm also one of the people
who's well-versed with the Eagles.

76
00:03:12,458 --> 00:03:14,494
-Do you have stocks?
-What, stocks?

77
00:03:14,561 --> 00:03:17,630
-For Hanhwa?
-They're doing great these days, sure.

78
00:03:17,697 --> 00:03:19,666
I graduated from the same school

79
00:03:19,732 --> 00:03:22,435
as Song Jin-woo and Chang Jong-hoon.

80
00:03:22,502 --> 00:03:24,103
The same middle school.

81
00:03:24,170 --> 00:03:25,872
So imagine how much I loved that team.

82
00:03:25,939 --> 00:03:28,908
In 2006, the year
when Hyun-jin joined the Eagles,

83
00:03:28,975 --> 00:03:30,777
they made it to the Korean Series.

84
00:03:30,843 --> 00:03:32,045
ROOKIE OF THE YEAR, GOLDEN GLOVE, MVP

85
00:03:32,111 --> 00:03:33,413
But they didn't win.

86
00:03:33,479 --> 00:03:37,183
<i>After 19 long years, in 2025…</i>

87
00:03:37,250 --> 00:03:38,818
RETURNING TO THE KOREAN SERIES
AFTER 19 YEARS!

88
00:03:38,885 --> 00:03:41,087
<i>The Eagles make it to the Korean Series</i>

89
00:03:41,154 --> 00:03:42,889
<i>after 19 long years!</i>

90
00:03:42,956 --> 00:03:45,592
<i>Your team went to the Korean Series</i>
<i>two years after your return.</i>

91
00:03:45,658 --> 00:03:47,026
<i>It's an incredible feat.</i>

92
00:03:47,093 --> 00:03:50,063
The first goal we set up
before the season began

93
00:03:50,129 --> 00:03:51,998
was to make it to the postseason.

94
00:03:52,065 --> 00:03:53,666
But there is a bit of regret left

95
00:03:53,733 --> 00:03:56,202
because we lost in the final round.

96
00:03:56,269 --> 00:03:59,639
Of course, professional athletes
are always thirsty for victory.

97
00:03:59,706 --> 00:04:02,909
I heard you sold the most uniforms
last year and this year.

98
00:04:02,976 --> 00:04:04,877
I'm not so sure about this year,

99
00:04:04,944 --> 00:04:05,979
but you're probably right.

100
00:04:08,448 --> 00:04:09,882
Wow.

101
00:04:09,949 --> 00:04:11,417
I hear one of our chefs

102
00:04:11,484 --> 00:04:14,087
-is known to be a huge fan of the Eagles.
-Really?

103
00:04:14,153 --> 00:04:16,723
-He said, "I couldn't even sleep well."
-Of course.

104
00:04:16,789 --> 00:04:18,291
Chef Sung-jun?

105
00:04:18,358 --> 00:04:20,526
It was a long time ago, 20 years ago.

106
00:04:20,593 --> 00:04:21,794
-Twenty years ago?
-Yes.

107
00:04:21,861 --> 00:04:25,465
That was when I became a baseball fan,
and a player had debuted in the same year.

108
00:04:25,531 --> 00:04:27,033
-In elementary school?
-It was Hyun-jin.

109
00:04:27,100 --> 00:04:28,801
-So you liked him since then?
-Yes, that was

110
00:04:28,868 --> 00:04:30,870
-when I became an Eagles fan.
-Oh, my.

111
00:04:30,937 --> 00:04:32,939
Have you been to the Korean Series?

112
00:04:33,006 --> 00:04:34,841
I have. I went and watched it.

113
00:04:35,475 --> 00:04:38,578
-Did you go and throw the first pitch?
-No, they didn't invite me.

114
00:04:39,812 --> 00:04:42,548
-Not anyone can do that.
-The honor isn't given to anyone.

115
00:04:42,615 --> 00:04:43,650
She has done it.

116
00:04:43,716 --> 00:04:45,318
-Who?
-Really?

117
00:04:45,385 --> 00:04:46,753
-I have…
-The first pitch?

118
00:04:46,819 --> 00:04:49,722
-Yes, for the Bears.
-She doesn't even know baseball.

119
00:04:49,789 --> 00:04:51,324
-When did you do it?
-This year.

120
00:04:51,391 --> 00:04:52,525
-This year?
-In the summer.

121
00:04:52,592 --> 00:04:53,793
Do you even know baseball?

122
00:04:53,860 --> 00:04:55,461
Of course. I enjoyed the game.

123
00:04:55,528 --> 00:04:57,196
-How many people play the game?
-What?

124
00:04:57,263 --> 00:04:58,665
-How many?
-Is that important?

125
00:04:59,666 --> 00:05:02,168
-There's a tip from the production crew.
-What is it?

126
00:05:02,235 --> 00:05:03,269
A TIP?

127
00:05:03,336 --> 00:05:05,538
The game she pitched for

128
00:05:05,605 --> 00:05:08,041
was between the Bears and the Eagles.

129
00:05:08,107 --> 00:05:10,476
At that time,
the Eagles were on a ten-game streak,

130
00:05:10,543 --> 00:05:13,980
but that game she pitched for
broke their run.

131
00:05:14,047 --> 00:05:15,615
-She is just…
-Oh, no.

132
00:05:15,682 --> 00:05:17,250
-…really wrong.
-Many fans must be watching.

133
00:05:17,317 --> 00:05:18,618
You aren't allowed near Daejeon.

134
00:05:18,685 --> 00:05:19,986
Don't go to Daejeon.

135
00:05:20,053 --> 00:05:21,954
Don't try to do anything there.

136
00:05:22,021 --> 00:05:23,456
Actually, these two players

137
00:05:23,523 --> 00:05:26,659
both played in the Major League
at the same time for eight years,

138
00:05:26,726 --> 00:05:27,927
but you two have played

139
00:05:27,994 --> 00:05:30,263
-against each other just once.
-Just once?

140
00:05:30,330 --> 00:05:35,868
Did you two shake hands
and greet each other before the game?

141
00:05:35,935 --> 00:05:36,869
CHUCKLE

142
00:05:36,936 --> 00:05:39,105
He was a friend until the day before,

143
00:05:39,172 --> 00:05:41,541
but on that day, he was just
a pitcher that happens to be Asian.

144
00:05:41,607 --> 00:05:43,176
JUST AN ASIAN PITCHER AT THE GAME

145
00:05:43,242 --> 00:05:44,744
-Just a pitcher for the other team.
-Yes.

146
00:05:44,811 --> 00:05:46,145
"An Asian pitcher."

147
00:05:46,212 --> 00:05:47,880
But you could've visited him
at the dugout.

148
00:05:47,947 --> 00:05:50,817
-Before the--
-"Hey, Hyun-jin. I'm here."

149
00:05:50,883 --> 00:05:52,719
"It's me. Long time no see."
You don't do that?

150
00:05:52,785 --> 00:05:54,087
This isn't amateur baseball.

151
00:05:54,754 --> 00:05:56,022
"Go easy on me!"

152
00:05:56,089 --> 00:05:57,256
They aren't amateurs!

153
00:05:57,323 --> 00:05:58,791
But they're so close!

154
00:05:58,858 --> 00:06:00,927
It's the biggest league in the world.

155
00:06:00,993 --> 00:06:03,763
Wouldn't your teammates have understood?

156
00:06:03,830 --> 00:06:04,664
What is it?

157
00:06:04,731 --> 00:06:06,699
When he struck out
and returned to the dugout,

158
00:06:07,266 --> 00:06:08,401
he cussed a whole lot.

159
00:06:09,902 --> 00:06:11,237
AWKWARD

160
00:06:11,304 --> 00:06:14,707
He must've said something like,
"I hate Hyun-jin!"

161
00:06:14,774 --> 00:06:16,142
-Do you remember that?
-Well…

162
00:06:18,311 --> 00:06:19,479
no one could hear it.

163
00:06:20,213 --> 00:06:21,714
-But he did swear.
-In his head.

164
00:06:21,781 --> 00:06:23,116
-In his head?
-Yes.

165
00:06:23,182 --> 00:06:24,584
REMEMBERING LIKE IT WAS YESTERDAY

166
00:06:24,650 --> 00:06:26,986
It was something like this.

167
00:06:27,053 --> 00:06:28,521
So he did.

168
00:06:28,588 --> 00:06:30,556
-He was provokingly good.
-He was?

169
00:06:30,623 --> 00:06:32,358
He was way too good.

170
00:06:32,425 --> 00:06:33,593
That's just a compliment.

171
00:06:33,659 --> 00:06:34,861
Do you remember that day?

172
00:06:34,927 --> 00:06:36,229
It was unforgettable.

173
00:06:37,463 --> 00:06:39,399
-The winner can't forget it.
-Listen to him.

174
00:06:39,465 --> 00:06:41,367
Were your pitches going well that day?

175
00:06:41,434 --> 00:06:44,570
-Korean residents must've cheered for you.
-It wasn't so bad.

176
00:06:45,138 --> 00:06:45,972
EYES SHUT TIGHT

177
00:06:47,240 --> 00:06:49,442
He did that against the leadoff hitter.

178
00:06:49,509 --> 00:06:51,210
Did you two meet after the game?

179
00:06:51,277 --> 00:06:52,178
Why would we do that?

180
00:06:52,745 --> 00:06:56,015
IT WAS GREAT TO SEE YOU,
BUT MAY WE NEVER MEET AGAIN

181
00:06:56,082 --> 00:06:57,250
Yes, why would we?

182
00:06:57,316 --> 00:06:58,885
I mean, you were in LA already.

183
00:06:58,951 --> 00:07:00,353
Didn't we meet?

184
00:07:00,420 --> 00:07:02,088
-You two met!
-Come on!

185
00:07:02,155 --> 00:07:03,356
He erased those memories.

186
00:07:03,423 --> 00:07:04,957
He forgot it altogether.

187
00:07:05,024 --> 00:07:07,593
He seemed extremely furious.

188
00:07:07,660 --> 00:07:09,128
-Of course.
-He must've been mad.

189
00:07:09,195 --> 00:07:12,231
It's time to peek into Hyun-jin's fridge,

190
00:07:12,298 --> 00:07:16,469
an athlete who'll celebrate
his 20th anniversary of debut next year.

191
00:07:16,536 --> 00:07:19,639
I hear you mostly stay in Daejeon
during the season.

192
00:07:19,705 --> 00:07:22,108
Then is this fridge from Daejeon?

193
00:07:22,175 --> 00:07:24,477
The season is over now,

194
00:07:24,544 --> 00:07:27,580
-so it's from my home in Ilsan.
-Your home in Ilsan.

195
00:07:27,647 --> 00:07:30,316
My parents and my parents-in-law

196
00:07:30,383 --> 00:07:32,452
-are all great cooks.
-I see.

197
00:07:32,518 --> 00:07:35,655
So you'll probably see
many dishes made by them.

198
00:07:35,721 --> 00:07:39,759
Is there something special you eat
when you have to be the starting pitcher

199
00:07:39,826 --> 00:07:41,160
during the season?

200
00:07:41,227 --> 00:07:43,663
-Let's say the game is at 6:30 p.m.
-Sure.

201
00:07:43,729 --> 00:07:45,932
Then I eat at noon

202
00:07:45,998 --> 00:07:47,900
and don't eat anything else
until the game ends.

203
00:07:47,967 --> 00:07:50,102
-Until the game ends?
-Right.

204
00:07:50,169 --> 00:07:54,173
I feel more at ease
when I play while feeling lighter.

205
00:07:54,240 --> 00:07:57,109
So that single meal
is quite important for me.

206
00:07:57,176 --> 00:07:59,745
I have to use lots of energy,

207
00:07:59,812 --> 00:08:03,249
-so I load up on carbs and protein.
-You need lots.

208
00:08:03,316 --> 00:08:04,617
GOTCHA

209
00:08:04,684 --> 00:08:06,352
You're not in season right now,

210
00:08:06,419 --> 00:08:08,354
so you must be with your wife quite often.

211
00:08:08,421 --> 00:08:11,958
I only spend time with her.

212
00:08:12,625 --> 00:08:14,360
I must be good to her in these times.

213
00:08:14,994 --> 00:08:16,162
HE'S RIGHT

214
00:08:16,229 --> 00:08:18,865
-His wife is a fellow announcer of mine.
-I know.

215
00:08:18,931 --> 00:08:21,033
-I heard you bullied her a lot.
-I didn't bully her!

216
00:08:22,168 --> 00:08:24,070
I wanted to guide her
as a senior announcer

217
00:08:24,136 --> 00:08:27,039
-with expertise in sports and help her!
-Why would you guide--

218
00:08:27,106 --> 00:08:28,441
Why do you consider that bullying?

219
00:08:28,508 --> 00:08:29,809
She said that herself.

220
00:08:29,876 --> 00:08:31,477
She told me that in the green room.

221
00:08:31,544 --> 00:08:35,548
-She's trying to say I was strict.
-"Strict"?

222
00:08:35,615 --> 00:08:36,716
Will you be strict with this?

223
00:08:36,782 --> 00:08:40,086
I will be.
I'll look through strictly and thoroughly.

224
00:08:40,152 --> 00:08:44,857
How does Hyun-jin, aka Korean Monster,
maintain his monstrous energy?

225
00:08:44,924 --> 00:08:47,693
-We present Hyun-jin's fridge!
-Fridge!

226
00:08:47,760 --> 00:08:50,997
We'll be fine today.
It was just as I expected.

227
00:08:51,497 --> 00:08:53,633
PRESENTING RYU HYUN-JIN'S FRIDGE

228
00:08:53,699 --> 00:08:55,701
-It's loaded.
-That's a lot of food.

229
00:08:55,768 --> 00:08:57,303
First, I see some meat.

230
00:08:57,370 --> 00:08:59,939
-And side dishes.
-You won't have to worry today.

231
00:09:00,006 --> 00:09:03,009
There's something notable
unlike other households.

232
00:09:03,075 --> 00:09:04,010
Can you show this?

233
00:09:04,076 --> 00:09:06,245
-Look at this. "Side Dishes for Adults."
-Hey.

234
00:09:06,312 --> 00:09:08,014
-"Side Dishes for Kids."
-For kids.

235
00:09:08,080 --> 00:09:10,182
"Ingredients to Use Up."

236
00:09:10,249 --> 00:09:12,451
These will probably expire soon.

237
00:09:12,518 --> 00:09:13,920
It's how we do it in restaurants.

238
00:09:13,986 --> 00:09:15,121
PROUD

239
00:09:15,187 --> 00:09:16,989
Let's take a look at each one of these.

240
00:09:17,056 --> 00:09:19,625
-It's very well-organized.
-First of all, pork.

241
00:09:19,692 --> 00:09:21,394
I see some pork over here,

242
00:09:21,460 --> 00:09:23,229
and beef over there.

243
00:09:23,296 --> 00:09:25,364
Do you enjoy both beef and pork?

244
00:09:25,431 --> 00:09:26,499
Yes, I like them all.

245
00:09:26,566 --> 00:09:28,601
-I prefer pork a little more.
-Pork.

246
00:09:28,668 --> 00:09:30,703
I see. Do you enjoy pork a little more?

247
00:09:30,770 --> 00:09:35,341
About 50% of what I eat in a year
must be pork.

248
00:09:35,408 --> 00:09:37,743
Do you ever get sick of it?

249
00:09:37,810 --> 00:09:40,513
How can anyone get sick of eating meat?

250
00:09:40,580 --> 00:09:42,381
That's my stance.

251
00:09:42,448 --> 00:09:44,517
-You must love it.
-Like no one gets sick of breathing.

252
00:09:44,584 --> 00:09:45,551
A TIP FROM THE CREW

253
00:09:45,618 --> 00:09:47,453
I received a tip from the production crew.

254
00:09:47,520 --> 00:09:50,823
-He told them that he doesn't eat a lot.
-You don't eat a lot?

255
00:09:50,890 --> 00:09:52,124
-Not a lot?
-That's quite shocking.

256
00:09:52,191 --> 00:09:53,960
You mean you don't eat a lot of beef?

257
00:09:54,026 --> 00:09:56,028
It must be a surprise,
but I can't eat a lot.

258
00:09:56,095 --> 00:09:58,397
-Surprisingly little?
-Yes, surprisingly little.

259
00:09:58,464 --> 00:10:01,601
-But you have to maintain your shape.
-That wasn't what I heard.

260
00:10:01,667 --> 00:10:04,036
Everyone I meet always says,

261
00:10:04,103 --> 00:10:06,772
"You don't seem to eat that much."

262
00:10:06,839 --> 00:10:09,041
I also don't like to eat
only one kind of food.

263
00:10:09,108 --> 00:10:10,910
-I see.
-So you need a variety.

264
00:10:10,977 --> 00:10:14,814
I like to order three to four dishes,
even though I can't eat a lot.

265
00:10:14,880 --> 00:10:16,415
I end up eating a bit of each.

266
00:10:16,482 --> 00:10:19,785
I even hear you do not eat
a whole bowl of rice. Is this true?

267
00:10:19,852 --> 00:10:22,521
I only finish the whole bowl
on the day when I pitch.

268
00:10:22,588 --> 00:10:23,556
-Really?
-Yes.

269
00:10:23,623 --> 00:10:25,791
Can you eat a whole fried chicken?

270
00:10:25,858 --> 00:10:27,059
-No, I can't.
-What?

271
00:10:27,126 --> 00:10:29,061
-You can't eat a chicken?
-He must get sick of it.

272
00:10:29,128 --> 00:10:31,297
I've never ordered just one fried chicken.

273
00:10:31,864 --> 00:10:34,100
I GET SICK OF EATING JUST THE CHICKEN

274
00:10:34,166 --> 00:10:37,269
He needs to eat some fried chicken,
some <i>tteokbokki</i>, and more.

275
00:10:37,970 --> 00:10:41,340
Let's take a look at the shelf
labeled "Side Dishes for Adults."

276
00:10:41,407 --> 00:10:43,509
I see some picked vegetables.

277
00:10:43,576 --> 00:10:46,912
My mother-in-law made
those delicious pickles.

278
00:10:46,979 --> 00:10:49,949
-<i>Gejang</i>, seasoned raw crab.
-<i>Gejang </i>in chili sauce.

279
00:10:50,016 --> 00:10:51,951
This looks delicious.

280
00:10:52,018 --> 00:10:54,220
My mother made that.

281
00:10:54,286 --> 00:10:56,355
-Your mother?
-Yes, my mother.

282
00:10:56,422 --> 00:10:59,492
It says "Seasoned Oyster Salad."

283
00:10:59,558 --> 00:11:02,862
That's also something my mother made.

284
00:11:02,928 --> 00:11:05,564
-That's…
-It looks so good!

285
00:11:05,631 --> 00:11:09,368
I mix that with a bit of rice
and a splash of sesame oil.

286
00:11:09,435 --> 00:11:11,804
-It's really good.
-It must be delicious.

287
00:11:11,871 --> 00:11:13,839
You said you don't eat a lot.

288
00:11:13,906 --> 00:11:16,308
-But if you're mixing that with rice…
-If he mixes that…

289
00:11:16,375 --> 00:11:17,743
I may add lots of those,

290
00:11:17,810 --> 00:11:20,146
but only a bit of rice.

291
00:11:20,212 --> 00:11:23,716
-All these pickles and side dishes…
-That would be too salty.

292
00:11:23,783 --> 00:11:25,484
You'll end up needing lots of water.

293
00:11:25,551 --> 00:11:27,820
But they aren't salty.

294
00:11:27,887 --> 00:11:28,954
-They aren't?
-No.

295
00:11:29,021 --> 00:11:31,524
By any chance,
is there anything your wife made?

296
00:11:31,590 --> 00:11:33,626
-No?
-Our kids…

297
00:11:33,693 --> 00:11:35,361
have been making
her life difficult lately.

298
00:11:35,428 --> 00:11:37,863
5-YEAR-OLD HYE-SEONG, 3-YEAR-OLD JUN-SANG

299
00:11:37,930 --> 00:11:42,468
She cooked all the meals
back when we were in America.

300
00:11:42,535 --> 00:11:45,271
But we're back in Korea,
and I'm not in season right now,

301
00:11:45,337 --> 00:11:48,307
so my mother-in-law
and my mother have been helping.

302
00:11:48,374 --> 00:11:50,342
-They're here to support you.
-With love.

303
00:11:50,409 --> 00:11:51,911
Is this seasoned soy sauce?

304
00:11:51,977 --> 00:11:53,846
My mother-in-law made that.

305
00:11:53,913 --> 00:11:55,481
I love deep-fried half-dried pollack.

306
00:11:55,548 --> 00:11:56,916
-I see.
-Half-dried pollack?

307
00:11:56,982 --> 00:11:59,218
Can you deep-fry those?
I thought you only braised those.

308
00:11:59,285 --> 00:12:01,053
I've never heard of it, either.

309
00:12:01,120 --> 00:12:03,055
This must be what he's frying.

310
00:12:03,122 --> 00:12:05,324
He must eat it with the sauce.

311
00:12:05,391 --> 00:12:06,459
Deep-fry these?

312
00:12:06,525 --> 00:12:09,161
I also had it for the first time
when I visited my mother-in-law.

313
00:12:09,228 --> 00:12:12,932
Once you dip the fry into that sauce,
it's game over.

314
00:12:12,998 --> 00:12:13,999
Gotcha.

315
00:12:14,066 --> 00:12:15,701
Do you enjoy deep-fried food?

316
00:12:15,768 --> 00:12:16,602
I do.

317
00:12:16,669 --> 00:12:19,472
I think I'd even enjoy a deep-fried shoe.

318
00:12:19,538 --> 00:12:22,842
-I love everything deep-fried.
-You told the production crew this.

319
00:12:22,908 --> 00:12:24,210
"I do not eat much,

320
00:12:24,276 --> 00:12:27,713
so the secret behind
keeping my shape is deep-fried food."

321
00:12:27,780 --> 00:12:30,750
It might be the reason
why I can stay in this shape.

322
00:12:31,484 --> 00:12:36,055
I don't eat a lot,
but I pick foods that have high calories.

323
00:12:36,122 --> 00:12:37,556
Is it related to his pitching speed?

324
00:12:37,623 --> 00:12:41,827
So deep-fried food was the secret
behind the Korean Monster's huge shape.

325
00:12:41,894 --> 00:12:43,329
Is there anything

326
00:12:43,395 --> 00:12:46,532
you never eat before a game?
Like a superstition?

327
00:12:46,599 --> 00:12:48,734
I had those things back in school.

328
00:12:48,801 --> 00:12:51,036
-On the day of the match, I…
-Eggs?

329
00:12:51,103 --> 00:12:53,239
-Eggs. So that I don't cause any nutmegs.
-Why eggs?

330
00:12:53,305 --> 00:12:55,674
-I see, to prevent any nutmegs.
-So that's why.

331
00:12:55,741 --> 00:12:57,409
-And <i>miyeok-guk</i>, seaweed soup.
-<i>Miyeok-guk.</i>

332
00:12:57,476 --> 00:12:59,078
-To avoid slipping.
-Right, since <i>miyeok</i> is slippery.

333
00:12:59,145 --> 00:13:01,380
Also, I didn't mix rice in soup.

334
00:13:01,447 --> 00:13:03,482
-Not to lose everything in a bowl.
-Right.

335
00:13:03,549 --> 00:13:05,518
I didn't know you really followed through.

336
00:13:05,584 --> 00:13:06,819
Do soccer players do that too?

337
00:13:06,886 --> 00:13:09,021
It's similar. <i>Miyeok-guk</i>, eggs,

338
00:13:09,088 --> 00:13:10,589
or anything that involves breaking.

339
00:13:10,656 --> 00:13:11,924
NO BREAKING

340
00:13:11,991 --> 00:13:14,527
Let's say someone broke their cup
while eating their meal.

341
00:13:14,593 --> 00:13:15,961
If we lose the game after that…

342
00:13:16,028 --> 00:13:17,263
-Is he in trouble?
-…he's dead meat.

343
00:13:17,329 --> 00:13:18,164
HOW DREADFUL

344
00:13:18,230 --> 00:13:19,498
-It's his fault?
-I'm serious.

345
00:13:19,565 --> 00:13:20,699
What about this?

346
00:13:20,766 --> 00:13:22,635
Is there something you eat that helps you

347
00:13:22,701 --> 00:13:23,803
-play better?
-There is.

348
00:13:23,869 --> 00:13:24,970
-There is.
-What could it be?

349
00:13:25,037 --> 00:13:27,973
There was something I ate for a year
until I got sick of it.

350
00:13:28,040 --> 00:13:29,809
-Yes?
-It was in 2019,

351
00:13:29,875 --> 00:13:33,646
when I had the best ERA and
had become an all-star with the Dodgers.

352
00:13:33,712 --> 00:13:37,783
On the day before the opening game,
I had some <i>gamja-tang</i>, pork backbone stew.

353
00:13:37,850 --> 00:13:39,985
-You had <i>gamja-tang </i>in LA?
-Yes.

354
00:13:40,052 --> 00:13:42,655
Then we won the opening game, so it began.

355
00:13:42,721 --> 00:13:44,290
-<i>Gamja-tang </i>every week?
-Yes.

356
00:13:44,356 --> 00:13:46,725
I always ate <i>gamja-tang</i>
on the day before I had to pitch.

357
00:13:46,792 --> 00:13:47,993
Once every five days.

358
00:13:48,060 --> 00:13:49,662
I was lucky throughout the year,

359
00:13:49,728 --> 00:13:51,397
so I couldn't get rid of that routine.

360
00:13:52,331 --> 00:13:56,535
Even when I played away games,
I went out of my way to find it.

361
00:13:56,602 --> 00:13:58,971
-That's a thing.
-It happens.

362
00:13:59,038 --> 00:14:02,541
-Did you have a food routine?
-Did you have one?

363
00:14:02,608 --> 00:14:04,877
Back in 2018,

364
00:14:04,944 --> 00:14:08,948
<i>I was on an on-base streak,</i>
<i>trying to break the record.</i>

365
00:14:09,014 --> 00:14:11,450
The thing is, I really love pho.

366
00:14:11,517 --> 00:14:14,186
I wouldn't have thought about it
if I had gone on base once or twice,

367
00:14:14,253 --> 00:14:16,255
but on that day, I got on base five times.

368
00:14:16,322 --> 00:14:17,823
-My gosh.
-In one game?

369
00:14:17,890 --> 00:14:19,859
That means
you reached the base every time.

370
00:14:19,925 --> 00:14:22,261
I had pho again the next day,
and the day after, and so on.

371
00:14:22,328 --> 00:14:24,697
-And I reached base twice, thrice…
-Twice and thrice.

372
00:14:24,763 --> 00:14:26,332
I ended up eating pho 48 days in a row.

373
00:14:27,800 --> 00:14:29,301
-I'd be sick of it.
-So would I.

374
00:14:29,368 --> 00:14:30,870
The vegetables.

375
00:14:30,936 --> 00:14:33,739
Perilla leaves, lettuce, and cilantro.

376
00:14:33,806 --> 00:14:36,942
-Do you like cilantro?
-Yes, I do.

377
00:14:37,509 --> 00:14:38,577
It's really good

378
00:14:38,644 --> 00:14:41,213
-when you add it to your pork wrap.
-It is.

379
00:14:41,280 --> 00:14:42,381
-That's why.
-They go well.

380
00:14:42,448 --> 00:14:44,016
I see fruit too. Do you like fruit?

381
00:14:44,083 --> 00:14:46,685
-I do.
-He likes fruit.

382
00:14:46,752 --> 00:14:50,723
Meanwhile, the beverages he keeps
are all zero-sugar.

383
00:14:50,789 --> 00:14:52,758
I may eat pizza and fried chicken,

384
00:14:52,825 --> 00:14:56,095
-but I drink zero-sugar drinks.
-He drinks zero-sugar beverages.

385
00:14:56,161 --> 00:14:57,396
I wanted to make a gesture

386
00:14:57,463 --> 00:15:00,266
and feel less guilty
about eating like that.

387
00:15:00,332 --> 00:15:02,134
Let's check out the freezer.

388
00:15:02,201 --> 00:15:04,403
What's this here?

389
00:15:04,470 --> 00:15:06,038
Is this squid?

390
00:15:06,105 --> 00:15:07,473
-Squid?
-My gosh.

391
00:15:07,539 --> 00:15:09,441
OVERWHELMINGLY HUGE

392
00:15:10,009 --> 00:15:12,478
HOW IS THAT SO BIG?

393
00:15:12,544 --> 00:15:14,013
-Wait, what's this?
-How much was that?

394
00:15:14,079 --> 00:15:15,814
WHAT IS IT?

395
00:15:15,881 --> 00:15:17,283
My gosh. No way.

396
00:15:17,349 --> 00:15:18,250
INGREDIENT 9: SABLEFISH

397
00:15:18,317 --> 00:15:19,919
Where do you get these?

398
00:15:19,985 --> 00:15:22,888
An acquaintance of mine
sent it to me as a present

399
00:15:22,955 --> 00:15:25,758
and told me to enjoy it with my wife
after a great season.

400
00:15:25,824 --> 00:15:27,893
I've never seen
bigfin reef squid this big before.

401
00:15:27,960 --> 00:15:30,963
-You can probably use it as a kite.
-You can.

402
00:15:31,030 --> 00:15:33,666
-Or maybe as a mask.
-A mask?

403
00:15:33,732 --> 00:15:35,801
-It was sent to me from Jeju Island.
-How amazing.

404
00:15:35,868 --> 00:15:38,871
I see shrimp,
Spanish mackerel, and mackerel.

405
00:15:38,938 --> 00:15:41,907
<i>Tteokbokki</i> and udon.

406
00:15:41,974 --> 00:15:44,543
-They must be his snacks.
-Yes, although he doesn't eat much.

407
00:15:44,610 --> 00:15:47,446
He doesn't eat much,
but he eats a variety of foods.

408
00:15:47,513 --> 00:15:48,914
A variety, but only a little.

409
00:15:48,981 --> 00:15:51,150
Hyun-jin is just like Hatnim.

410
00:15:51,216 --> 00:15:53,252
That was all for his fridge!

411
00:15:53,319 --> 00:15:55,688
FINISHED INSPECTING THE FRIDGE
FOR THE MALE HATNIM

412
00:15:55,754 --> 00:15:57,489
Before we decide on the matches,

413
00:15:57,556 --> 00:15:59,892
let me tell you
how important these will be.

414
00:15:59,959 --> 00:16:01,694
The matches we hold with their two fridges

415
00:16:01,760 --> 00:16:06,932
<i>will be the final rounds</i>
<i>for the 2025 regular season.</i>

416
00:16:06,999 --> 00:16:10,769
And based on the results
after the regular season,

417
00:16:10,836 --> 00:16:14,406
we're going to decide
which one of them was the best this year.

418
00:16:14,473 --> 00:16:18,110
Only the top five chefs are allowed
to compete in the championship.

419
00:16:18,177 --> 00:16:19,878
IS THAT SO?

420
00:16:19,945 --> 00:16:21,213
What will the rest do?

421
00:16:21,280 --> 00:16:22,314
Become cheerleaders?

422
00:16:22,381 --> 00:16:25,884
The championship will be held
just like the baseball playoffs.

423
00:16:25,951 --> 00:16:28,120
<i>We'll hold four matches in total.</i>

424
00:16:28,187 --> 00:16:30,956
<i>Fifth place fights fourth place,</i>

425
00:16:31,023 --> 00:16:32,791
<i>and the winner fights third place.</i>

426
00:16:32,858 --> 00:16:34,259
<i>That winner fights second place,</i>

427
00:16:34,326 --> 00:16:38,297
<i>and the winner after that</i>
<i>will fight against first place.</i>

428
00:16:38,364 --> 00:16:39,598
Like taking titles.

429
00:16:39,665 --> 00:16:41,266
-Do you get it?
-You'll keep fighting as you go up.

430
00:16:41,333 --> 00:16:44,169
Let's find out the current ranking.
Show us!

431
00:16:44,236 --> 00:16:45,704
They'll show us the ranking?

432
00:16:45,771 --> 00:16:47,439
This is the current ranking.

433
00:16:47,506 --> 00:16:51,610
Before today's final rounds,
Hyun-suk is currently in first place.

434
00:16:51,677 --> 00:16:53,245
-Poong holds second place.
-Second?

435
00:16:53,312 --> 00:16:55,647
In third place, Ho-young and Jong-won.

436
00:16:55,714 --> 00:16:58,817
Tying in fifth place
are Eun-yeong, Nam-no, and Sung-jun.

437
00:16:58,884 --> 00:17:01,387
-He's the second place?
-I don't see Sam here.

438
00:17:01,453 --> 00:17:02,654
That's odd. I'm not on it.

439
00:17:02,721 --> 00:17:05,624
He had to visit Italy
in the middle of the year, so…

440
00:17:05,691 --> 00:17:09,495
Even if you win on this episode
or the next, you only get one star.

441
00:17:09,561 --> 00:17:12,631
-We already know he won't make it.
-He's not on the list.

442
00:17:12,698 --> 00:17:15,667
I'll come prepared for the next season.

443
00:17:15,734 --> 00:17:16,702
I'll do my best.

444
00:17:16,769 --> 00:17:19,438
-Only the first place secured a spot.
-It's an overwhelming win.

445
00:17:19,505 --> 00:17:22,408
Only the top five chefs get to move on.

446
00:17:22,474 --> 00:17:24,576
If the chefs hold
the same number of stars,

447
00:17:24,643 --> 00:17:28,614
the one with fewer losses
will get to take the higher ranking.

448
00:17:28,680 --> 00:17:30,849
-Let's find out.
-When they have the same number?

449
00:17:30,916 --> 00:17:32,951
CURRENT RANKING (2025 SEASON)

450
00:17:33,018 --> 00:17:36,055
-You lost 14 times.
-When did that happen?

451
00:17:36,121 --> 00:17:37,322
When did I lose all that?

452
00:17:37,389 --> 00:17:40,459
<i>Eun-yeong, Nam-no, and Sung-jun</i>
<i>all have five stars.</i>

453
00:17:40,526 --> 00:17:42,995
<i>If the number of stars</i>
<i>remain the same after the last match,</i>

454
00:17:43,062 --> 00:17:46,231
<i>the chef with the fewest losses,</i>
<i>Eun-yeong will make the cut.</i>

455
00:17:46,298 --> 00:17:47,900
If Sung-jun wants to make it,

456
00:17:47,966 --> 00:17:50,369
both Eun-yeong and Nam-no must lose.

457
00:17:50,436 --> 00:17:52,938
Only you have to win for you to continue.

458
00:17:53,005 --> 00:17:55,841
-It's not so likely.
-The probability is against you.

459
00:17:55,908 --> 00:17:58,477
I'll show you that I can win
despite my lowest winning rate.

460
00:17:58,544 --> 00:18:00,979
-This episode and the next…
-I have to win this week.

461
00:18:01,046 --> 00:18:02,948
-…are important. You must win.
-You're right.

462
00:18:03,015 --> 00:18:05,084
Try your best, guys.

463
00:18:05,150 --> 00:18:06,485
SPEECHLESS AT THE BRINK OF DROPPING OUT

464
00:18:06,552 --> 00:18:07,986
-Yes, sir.
-Okay!

465
00:18:08,053 --> 00:18:12,357
What's more important is that
your fates lie in the hands of these two.

466
00:18:12,424 --> 00:18:13,392
I'll do my very best today.

467
00:18:13,459 --> 00:18:16,161
-Will you make it to the championship?
-I'm nervous.

468
00:18:16,228 --> 00:18:20,466
Let's find out what Hyun-jin ordered.

469
00:18:20,532 --> 00:18:22,501
Show us his orders!

470
00:18:22,568 --> 00:18:26,004
A Victorious and Porky Pregame Meal.

471
00:18:26,071 --> 00:18:28,607
-A pork dish?
-It's a pork dish.

472
00:18:28,674 --> 00:18:30,843
A Victorious and Porky Pregame Meal.
What's the order?

473
00:18:30,909 --> 00:18:34,480
I eat only one meal
on the day before my games.

474
00:18:34,546 --> 00:18:36,815
If I eat a particular dish and win,

475
00:18:36,882 --> 00:18:39,451
-I'll continue to eat the same thing.
-Right.

476
00:18:39,518 --> 00:18:44,423
So I want a pork dish that'll give me
lots of energy before the game.

477
00:18:44,490 --> 00:18:45,357
I see.

478
00:18:45,424 --> 00:18:46,692
The winning chef must

479
00:18:46,758 --> 00:18:49,928
-travel all throughout the year for him…
-You have to go.

480
00:18:49,995 --> 00:18:52,131
-You should.
-…and make the same dish.

481
00:18:52,197 --> 00:18:53,432
Even for away games.

482
00:18:53,499 --> 00:18:56,301
-It would be an honor.
-A designated chef for the Eagles.

483
00:18:56,368 --> 00:18:57,903
What's the second order?

484
00:18:57,970 --> 00:18:59,972
-Korean Deep-Fry Monster.
-Korean Deep-Fry Monster.

485
00:19:00,038 --> 00:19:02,007
I really love deep-fried food,

486
00:19:02,074 --> 00:19:05,677
so I want to eat something deep-fried,
which will help me stay in this shape.

487
00:19:05,744 --> 00:19:07,279
THE TOP PLAYER'S SPECIAL DIET

488
00:19:07,346 --> 00:19:09,581
He keeps emphasizing
that he doesn't eat a lot,

489
00:19:09,648 --> 00:19:11,917
that deep-fried food
helps him keep his shape.

490
00:19:11,984 --> 00:19:13,118
Who'll jump in first?

491
00:19:13,185 --> 00:19:15,954
We all know the number of stars
and the current ranking.

492
00:19:16,021 --> 00:19:17,556
Who wants a spot first?

493
00:19:17,623 --> 00:19:19,258
-Well, I should go.
-You should.

494
00:19:19,324 --> 00:19:23,729
It's already an honor
that I can cook for Hyun-jin.

495
00:19:23,795 --> 00:19:25,297
And even better if you win a star.

496
00:19:25,364 --> 00:19:27,599
I'll make
A Victorious and Porky Pregame Meal.

497
00:19:27,666 --> 00:19:29,835
-I see.
-The pork round. Okay.

498
00:19:29,902 --> 00:19:33,172
A huge fan of the Eagles,
Chef Sung-jun joins the round first.

499
00:19:33,238 --> 00:19:34,806
In that case,

500
00:19:34,873 --> 00:19:37,409
-I'll challenge him.
-The pork round?

501
00:19:37,476 --> 00:19:39,444
But you two have the same number of stars!

502
00:19:39,511 --> 00:19:43,515
-It means one of you will get eliminated.
-One will get eliminated no matter what.

503
00:19:43,582 --> 00:19:45,184
-One of you may move on.
-We must do this.

504
00:19:46,084 --> 00:19:48,520
I want to make a pork dish
as the official piggy of the show.

505
00:19:48,587 --> 00:19:50,222
-What?
-That's way too advantageous.

506
00:19:50,289 --> 00:19:53,091
I already know everything
about every pork cut.

507
00:19:53,158 --> 00:19:54,660
-Do you?
-Shoulder.

508
00:19:54,726 --> 00:19:56,528
-Ham.
-Ham.

509
00:19:56,595 --> 00:19:57,763
-Pork neck.
-All right.

510
00:19:57,829 --> 00:19:59,898
Next, who'll deep-fry something?

511
00:19:59,965 --> 00:20:01,266
Does anyone want to deep-fry?

512
00:20:01,333 --> 00:20:02,167
I'LL GO!

513
00:20:02,234 --> 00:20:04,870
Poong is in with his ten stars!

514
00:20:04,937 --> 00:20:07,072
-He looks so relaxed.
-The sole second place.

515
00:20:07,139 --> 00:20:09,608
-Deep-fried dishes…
-He's good at that.

516
00:20:09,675 --> 00:20:11,009
<i>…are one of my specialties.</i>

517
00:20:11,076 --> 00:20:12,911
<i>So I'll join that round.</i>

518
00:20:12,978 --> 00:20:14,780
-I'll deep-fry everything.
-Will you?

519
00:20:14,846 --> 00:20:16,248
-Fry everything for him.
-Sure.

520
00:20:16,315 --> 00:20:19,318
-What if he fries a baseball?
-A baseball?

521
00:20:19,384 --> 00:20:24,122
<i>If he wins, he'll secure his place</i>
<i>as the sole second place.</i>

522
00:20:24,189 --> 00:20:27,426
-Who'll fight him and deep-fry something?
-Deep-fry.

523
00:20:27,492 --> 00:20:29,628
-I'll deep-fry something.
-Eun-yeong!

524
00:20:29,695 --> 00:20:31,496
Eun-yeong who is in co-fifth place.

525
00:20:31,563 --> 00:20:32,764
We all may have eight stars,

526
00:20:32,831 --> 00:20:34,900
but it's right that I move up
with my win rate.

527
00:20:34,967 --> 00:20:35,901
Let's curse her.

528
00:20:35,968 --> 00:20:37,836
In order to do so,
I must win another star,

529
00:20:37,903 --> 00:20:39,871
and Poong may be my easiest opponent here.

530
00:20:40,505 --> 00:20:42,174
DOES SHE THINK I'M EASY TO BEAT?

531
00:20:42,241 --> 00:20:43,642
-I have to win.
-Is it a free win?

532
00:20:43,709 --> 00:20:45,077
DO NOT TAKE HIM AS A JOKE!

533
00:20:45,143 --> 00:20:48,413
She thinks I'm an easy opponent, right?
All right. I understand.

534
00:20:48,480 --> 00:20:50,816
These are both important rounds.

535
00:20:50,882 --> 00:20:53,385
First, let us begin the 15-minute cook-off

536
00:20:53,452 --> 00:20:55,921
between Chef Sung-jun and Chef Nam-no!

537
00:20:55,988 --> 00:20:57,889
WHO'LL BE THE FIRST ONE TO GET ELIMINATED?

538
00:20:58,957 --> 00:21:03,362
<i>Let us begin the first cook-off</i>
<i>with ingredients from Hyun-jin's fridge.</i>

539
00:21:03,428 --> 00:21:08,300
Two men who love pork as much as Hyun-jin
are up for the challenge.

540
00:21:08,367 --> 00:21:09,835
They're currently tied for fifth place.

541
00:21:09,901 --> 00:21:13,238
During their journey on the show,

542
00:21:13,305 --> 00:21:15,107
<i>they worked together like brothers.</i>

543
00:21:15,173 --> 00:21:17,142
TOGETHER IN JOY

544
00:21:17,209 --> 00:21:18,877
<i>-They had the same hair,</i>
<i>-Yes!</i>

545
00:21:18,944 --> 00:21:21,780
<i>-…and they were on the same team.</i>
<i>-They went through many ups and downs.</i>

546
00:21:21,847 --> 00:21:24,216
But they must now face each other.

547
00:21:24,283 --> 00:21:26,985
The loser gets eliminated immediately.

548
00:21:27,052 --> 00:21:28,320
THIS ROUND'S LOSER IS ELIMINATED

549
00:21:28,387 --> 00:21:31,690
-One of them will join you, Sam.
-One of the two?

550
00:21:31,757 --> 00:21:34,893
And if you win this round,
you immediately go to the championship…

551
00:21:34,960 --> 00:21:36,228
…in your dreams.

552
00:21:37,462 --> 00:21:40,165
-But you must wait for Eun-yeong's round.
-That's true.

553
00:21:40,232 --> 00:21:43,235
<i>-The winner still might get eliminated.</i>
<i>-That's a possibility.</i>

554
00:21:43,302 --> 00:21:45,270
<i>But you have to win to even get a chance.</i>

555
00:21:45,337 --> 00:21:47,306
-It's a cruel fate for the twins.
-It is.

556
00:21:47,372 --> 00:21:49,508
How did they end up like this?

557
00:21:49,574 --> 00:21:52,244
In baseball, we often let the data speak.

558
00:21:52,311 --> 00:21:55,380
So what's the win-loss record
over three rounds between the two?

559
00:21:55,447 --> 00:21:57,649
Nam-no has won all three rounds.

560
00:21:57,716 --> 00:21:59,251
SURPRISED

561
00:21:59,985 --> 00:22:01,720
I'm on a roll!

562
00:22:01,787 --> 00:22:03,955
<i>-That was why he smiled.</i>
<i>-He smiled for a reason.</i>

563
00:22:04,022 --> 00:22:06,391
<i>He always did well against Sung-jun.</i>

564
00:22:06,458 --> 00:22:07,793
-You were his prey!
-All three rounds.

565
00:22:07,859 --> 00:22:09,428
I'M EXCITED TO PREY ON HIM

566
00:22:09,494 --> 00:22:11,163
There's this saying in Korean baseball.

567
00:22:11,229 --> 00:22:12,964
"The Fall Man."

568
00:22:13,031 --> 00:22:14,099
Yes.

569
00:22:14,166 --> 00:22:17,069
Some players are extremely good
in the fall season.

570
00:22:17,135 --> 00:22:18,003
That's me.

571
00:22:19,338 --> 00:22:20,839
It's now winter.

572
00:22:20,906 --> 00:22:22,974
-It's not fall.
-It's December.

573
00:22:23,041 --> 00:22:24,376
-It's over.
-It's winter.

574
00:22:24,443 --> 00:22:27,546
I'm a key player
who's good at important games.

575
00:22:27,612 --> 00:22:29,581
-Isn't that what you call a star?
-Right.

576
00:22:29,648 --> 00:22:32,050
-Stars are good at big games.
-Of course.

577
00:22:32,117 --> 00:22:33,251
I win when I must.

578
00:22:33,318 --> 00:22:34,953
What if he loses again after saying that?

579
00:22:35,020 --> 00:22:36,688
-I know.
-A crushing defeat.

580
00:22:36,755 --> 00:22:40,759
If you win this round
and Eun-yeong loses her round,

581
00:22:40,826 --> 00:22:44,596
you could go to the championship,
and there, if you win against everyone…

582
00:22:44,663 --> 00:22:45,597
That would be fun.

583
00:22:45,664 --> 00:22:47,499
The winner of both <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>
and <i>Chef & My Fridge.</i>

584
00:22:47,566 --> 00:22:50,035
-You're right.
-You'd see news articles on you.

585
00:22:50,102 --> 00:22:51,336
APPALLED

586
00:22:51,403 --> 00:22:53,638
And everything began with Hyun-jin!

587
00:22:53,705 --> 00:22:54,873
Yes, exactly.

588
00:22:54,940 --> 00:22:56,675
PRECISELY!

589
00:22:57,609 --> 00:22:59,611
CHEF SUNG-JUN'S INGREDIENTS:
PORK SHOULDER, PORK NECK, LEMON

590
00:22:59,678 --> 00:23:01,680
CILANTRO, PAPRIKA, RADISH, GREEN ONION,
CHEONGYANG PEPPER, SESAME OIL, AND MORE

591
00:23:01,747 --> 00:23:02,948
WHAT'S SUNG-JUN'S PORK DISH?

592
00:23:03,014 --> 00:23:05,016
This is the name of my dish.

593
00:23:05,083 --> 00:23:07,919
Nam-no Can't Pig Out Like Me.

594
00:23:07,986 --> 00:23:10,455
CHEF KWON SUNG-JUN
NAM-NO CAN'T PIG OUT LIKE ME

595
00:23:10,522 --> 00:23:12,090
That's so immature.

596
00:23:12,157 --> 00:23:13,358
"Pig out"?

597
00:23:13,425 --> 00:23:15,961
That's something people say.

598
00:23:16,027 --> 00:23:17,763
-He's provoking him.
-Yes.

599
00:23:17,829 --> 00:23:21,066
-I'll use pork neck to make skewers.
-Pork neck.

600
00:23:21,133 --> 00:23:22,267
-Skewers?
-Skewers?

601
00:23:22,334 --> 00:23:24,002
I'll serve it with a side he'll like,

602
00:23:24,069 --> 00:23:25,804
fresh cilantro salad.

603
00:23:25,871 --> 00:23:27,706
-Cilantro.
-Seasoned cilantro.

604
00:23:27,773 --> 00:23:30,108
Also, there's a piece of information
only I know.

605
00:23:30,175 --> 00:23:32,577
Hyun-jin requires soup whenever he eats.

606
00:23:32,644 --> 00:23:34,045
REALLY?

607
00:23:34,112 --> 00:23:35,847
-Is that right?
-Yes.

608
00:23:35,914 --> 00:23:37,282
He needs soup.

609
00:23:37,349 --> 00:23:40,419
That was something he didn't share
when we looked at his fridge.

610
00:23:40,485 --> 00:23:43,088
I was already aware of that,
so I'm using my family's recipe

611
00:23:43,155 --> 00:23:45,891
to make
Chungcheong-do style <i>jeotguk-jjigae.</i>

612
00:23:46,591 --> 00:23:48,727
Are you making <i>jeotguk-jjigae?</i>

613
00:23:48,794 --> 00:23:50,095
I'll make that today.

614
00:23:50,162 --> 00:23:51,830
What's <i>jeotguk-jjigae?</i>

615
00:23:51,897 --> 00:23:55,300
It's a soup
made with salted shrimp and tofu.

616
00:23:55,367 --> 00:23:56,802
He'll use salted shrimp.

617
00:23:56,868 --> 00:24:00,472
Hyun-jin seems unaware
of what <i>jeotguk-jjigae</i> is.

618
00:24:00,539 --> 00:24:02,641
I believe he was born in Incheon.

619
00:24:02,707 --> 00:24:05,744
You'll love <i>jeotguk-jjigae</i>
from today onward.

620
00:24:05,811 --> 00:24:08,013
Today is the last round if you lose today.

621
00:24:08,079 --> 00:24:09,981
-That's true.
-It'll be the last round.

622
00:24:10,048 --> 00:24:12,451
-The end of the 2025 season.
-It's the last one.

623
00:24:12,517 --> 00:24:14,286
Sung-jun's last dish, <i>jeotguk-jjigae.</i>

624
00:24:14,853 --> 00:24:18,023
WILL IT BECOME THE LAST DISH HE MAKES?

625
00:24:18,423 --> 00:24:20,692
CHEF NAM-NO'S INGREDIENTS:
PORK SHOULDER, SEASONED OYSTER SALAD

626
00:24:20,759 --> 00:24:23,028
GEJANG WITH CHILI SAUCE, PERILLA LEAF
FRIED POLLACK SOY SAUCE, APPLE, AND MORE

627
00:24:23,094 --> 00:24:24,796
The dish I prepared is called

628
00:24:24,863 --> 00:24:27,532
Sung-jun, Stop Pigging Out.

629
00:24:27,599 --> 00:24:29,201
-Stop Pigging Out.
-Stop Pigging Out.

630
00:24:29,267 --> 00:24:31,536
Sung-jun, Stop Pigging Out.

631
00:24:31,603 --> 00:24:34,639
-Stop Pigging Out.
-Nam-no must've been upset.

632
00:24:34,706 --> 00:24:36,842
I'm going to make noodles

633
00:24:36,908 --> 00:24:38,610
with your favorite side dish, <i>gejang.</i>

634
00:24:38,677 --> 00:24:40,545
-<i>Gejang</i> noodles?
-Noodles made with <i>gejang.</i>

635
00:24:40,612 --> 00:24:41,446
That sounds good.

636
00:24:41,513 --> 00:24:44,316
<i>I'll mix</i> naengmyeon <i>broth and fruit</i>
<i>to make the soup</i>

637
00:24:44,382 --> 00:24:46,151
to help with digestion.

638
00:24:46,218 --> 00:24:48,587
And I'll use seasoned oyster salad
to make the side dish.

639
00:24:48,653 --> 00:24:50,422
Lastly, I'll make my main dish

640
00:24:50,489 --> 00:24:51,890
with pork shoulder,

641
00:24:51,957 --> 00:24:54,159
seasoned in <i>doenjang</i>
and garlic <i>galbi</i> sauce.

642
00:24:54,226 --> 00:24:58,797
I'll make something to fire you up
before you go up on the mound.

643
00:24:58,864 --> 00:25:02,434
Upon hearing the explanation,

644
00:25:03,134 --> 00:25:06,137
I'm more intrigued by Chef Nam-no's dish.

645
00:25:06,204 --> 00:25:09,374
I have a feeling that
the <i>jeotguk-jjigae</i> will be

646
00:25:09,441 --> 00:25:11,676
the decisive factor in this match.

647
00:25:11,743 --> 00:25:14,513
His <i>jeotguk-jjigae</i> is a huge variable.

648
00:25:14,579 --> 00:25:17,315
-What will he do?
-He doesn't even know what it is.

649
00:25:17,382 --> 00:25:19,818
-It's my family's recipe, though.
-The family's recipe. Good.

650
00:25:19,885 --> 00:25:23,321
His <i>Jeotguk-jjigae</i> will be
the most decisive factor today.

651
00:25:23,388 --> 00:25:27,792
And now, let us begin the cook-off
just for Ryu Hyun-jin.

652
00:25:27,859 --> 00:25:31,029
A COOK-OFF TO HELP HYUN-JIN
STAND ON THE MOUND

653
00:25:31,096 --> 00:25:33,198
"Stop acting cheeky
like you can pig out, Sung-jun."

654
00:25:33,265 --> 00:25:35,500
The piggy, Chef Yoon Nam-no.

655
00:25:35,567 --> 00:25:36,668
Piggy!

656
00:25:36,735 --> 00:25:38,436
But the other piggy, Kwon Sung-jun,

657
00:25:38,503 --> 00:25:40,906
says Nam-no has nothing on him.

658
00:25:40,972 --> 00:25:43,508
This is their last opportunity
to move on to the championship.

659
00:25:43,575 --> 00:25:47,012
Let their 15-minute cook-off begin!

660
00:25:48,113 --> 00:25:49,247
Let's go!

661
00:25:49,881 --> 00:25:50,849
THE SALUTING ROUTINE

662
00:25:50,916 --> 00:25:52,117
Let's do this!

663
00:25:53,451 --> 00:25:56,388
For one of them, this will be
the last dish he cooks this year.

664
00:25:56,821 --> 00:25:59,057
PIGGY YOON USES PORK SHOULDER

665
00:25:59,124 --> 00:26:01,826
He's coating pork shoulder
with curry powder.

666
00:26:01,893 --> 00:26:04,729
-Why is he using curry powder with meat?
-Are you eliminating the smell?

667
00:26:04,796 --> 00:26:07,832
-It eliminates all the funky smells.
-The weird smells?

668
00:26:07,899 --> 00:26:10,435
-Noodles.
-He grabs some noodles.

669
00:26:10,502 --> 00:26:12,037
Why is he cooking them so soon?

670
00:26:12,103 --> 00:26:14,172
I'm going to serve them cold.

671
00:26:14,239 --> 00:26:16,141
It's a cold dish?

672
00:26:16,207 --> 00:26:18,877
You both have 15 minutes.

673
00:26:19,444 --> 00:26:22,080
THE KWON FAMILY RECIPE:
STIR-FRY PORK SHOULDER, GARLIC…

674
00:26:22,147 --> 00:26:24,215
He chopped the pork shoulder
and threw that in.

675
00:26:25,216 --> 00:26:26,318
Onions.

676
00:26:26,952 --> 00:26:30,255
That's odd. <i>Jeotguk-jjigae</i> is usually made

677
00:26:30,322 --> 00:26:31,823
with just zucchini and salted shrimp.

678
00:26:31,890 --> 00:26:33,792
But his family's recipe must be different.

679
00:26:33,858 --> 00:26:35,760
Yes, that must be the case.

680
00:26:36,595 --> 00:26:37,629
Soy sauce?

681
00:26:37,696 --> 00:26:38,763
It's like <i>jjamppong.</i>

682
00:26:38,830 --> 00:26:40,865
Wait, he added soy sauce?

683
00:26:40,932 --> 00:26:42,367
-<i>Jeotguk </i>is…
-That's not <i>jeotguk.</i>

684
00:26:42,434 --> 00:26:43,501
Just a little bit.

685
00:26:43,568 --> 00:26:44,936
-<i>Jeotguk?</i>
-That's soy sauce-<i>guk.</i>

686
00:26:45,003 --> 00:26:47,205
-It's soy sauce-<i>guk.</i>
<i>-Jeotguk</i> is usually a clear soup

687
00:26:47,272 --> 00:26:49,207
-seasoned only with salted shrimp.
-Yes.

688
00:26:49,274 --> 00:26:50,375
-And some tofu.
-Just a bit.

689
00:26:50,442 --> 00:26:51,476
It needs salted shrimp.

690
00:26:51,543 --> 00:26:52,377
Just a bit.

691
00:26:52,444 --> 00:26:53,979
ENJOYING THE LIVE PERFORMANCE

692
00:26:54,045 --> 00:26:56,615
-Isn't that just <i>jeongol?</i>
-I added just a bit.

693
00:26:56,681 --> 00:26:59,250
-It's pork <i>jeongol.</i>
-His family recipe must be different.

694
00:26:59,317 --> 00:27:00,919
Stop bashing my family.

695
00:27:00,986 --> 00:27:03,421
-We can't mess with his family.
-We can't.

696
00:27:03,488 --> 00:27:05,390
2. MAKE CHILI OIL WITH GREEN ONION,
RED PEPPER POWDER, AND GARLIC

697
00:27:05,457 --> 00:27:07,292
I think he's making chili oil.

698
00:27:07,359 --> 00:27:08,727
Is he making chili oil?

699
00:27:08,793 --> 00:27:10,328
-I am.
-I see.

700
00:27:10,895 --> 00:27:12,364
PIGGY YOON IS READY TO PEEL AN APPLE

701
00:27:12,764 --> 00:27:13,665
PEEL PEEL PEEL

702
00:27:13,732 --> 00:27:16,368
Look at Chef Nam-no's
amazing knife skills.

703
00:27:16,434 --> 00:27:18,503
-He's spinning it around.
-Nam-no shows off his skills!

704
00:27:18,570 --> 00:27:22,307
The ladies who work in the kitchen
of a nightclub are really good at that!

705
00:27:22,374 --> 00:27:24,576
He'd be a great staff member there.

706
00:27:25,143 --> 00:27:26,378
AMAZED

707
00:27:26,444 --> 00:27:29,280
Someone who can perform like him
should make it to the championship.

708
00:27:29,347 --> 00:27:31,383
-He's good at spinning it around.
-Yes.

709
00:27:31,449 --> 00:27:33,451
-His knife skills are amazing.
-How cool.

710
00:27:33,518 --> 00:27:36,221
He's doing it again!

711
00:27:36,287 --> 00:27:37,389
Let's go!

712
00:27:37,455 --> 00:27:38,523
THE GOOD VIBES PIGGY

713
00:27:39,090 --> 00:27:41,660
SO SKILLFUL

714
00:27:41,726 --> 00:27:44,396
Chef Sung-jun is being too calm

715
00:27:44,462 --> 00:27:46,698
while Nam-no gives
a wonderful performance.

716
00:27:46,765 --> 00:27:48,733
That's a pear.

717
00:27:48,800 --> 00:27:50,035
A pear.

718
00:27:50,802 --> 00:27:52,604
-What's that?
-What is that?

719
00:27:52,671 --> 00:27:54,439
-Broth? <i>Naengmyeon</i> broth.
-<i>Naengmyeon</i> broth.

720
00:27:54,506 --> 00:27:58,109
-He had <i>naengmyeon</i> broth.
-He's blending it with fruit.

721
00:27:58,176 --> 00:28:02,714
It'll turn into soup that has
both sweetness and acidity.

722
00:28:02,781 --> 00:28:05,116
Is that for the <i>gejang</i> noodles?

723
00:28:05,183 --> 00:28:08,019
-Yes!
-It must be savory and delicious.

724
00:28:08,086 --> 00:28:10,488
He's peeling radish!

725
00:28:10,555 --> 00:28:11,690
WILL PIGGY KWON PERFORM TOO?

726
00:28:12,691 --> 00:28:14,559
That's how he's doing it.

727
00:28:14,626 --> 00:28:15,460
Come on!

728
00:28:15,527 --> 00:28:16,394
DISAPPOINTED

729
00:28:16,461 --> 00:28:18,763
-What will he do?
-He's far behind Nam-no.

730
00:28:18,830 --> 00:28:21,566
And he peeled it too thick.

731
00:28:21,633 --> 00:28:23,134
PIGGY YOON WINS IN THE PERFORMANCE

732
00:28:23,201 --> 00:28:25,670
Wait, does <i>jeotguk-jjigae</i>
usually come with radish?

733
00:28:25,737 --> 00:28:27,072
It does.

734
00:28:27,138 --> 00:28:30,408
My family only made it
with salted shrimp, zucchini, and tofu.

735
00:28:30,475 --> 00:28:32,444
The recipe differs by family.

736
00:28:32,510 --> 00:28:33,878
STOPPING THE CRITICISMS

737
00:28:33,945 --> 00:28:35,246
-We can't mess with the family.
-It differs.

738
00:28:35,313 --> 00:28:36,514
The recipe differs by family.

739
00:28:36,581 --> 00:28:39,284
-It's his family, so I'm left speechless.
-I have nothing to say.

740
00:28:39,984 --> 00:28:41,352
THE KEY INGREDIENT, SALTED SHRIMP

741
00:28:41,419 --> 00:28:43,755
-Salted shrimp goes in.
-He should add that much.

742
00:28:43,822 --> 00:28:45,123
-Do you need that much?
-Yes.

743
00:28:45,190 --> 00:28:46,424
Wouldn't it be too salty?

744
00:28:46,491 --> 00:28:47,325
That's a lot.

745
00:28:47,392 --> 00:28:48,626
CHOPPING

746
00:28:48,693 --> 00:28:50,695
It'll taste spicy too.

747
00:28:50,762 --> 00:28:51,963
Are you good with spicy food?

748
00:28:52,030 --> 00:28:54,232
-I like it.
-He likes spicy food. I'm glad.

749
00:28:54,299 --> 00:28:55,767
The skewers.

750
00:28:55,834 --> 00:28:57,569
Sung-jun is about to make skewers!

751
00:28:57,635 --> 00:28:59,971
-Is he using pork neck?
-The skewers!

752
00:29:00,038 --> 00:29:02,373
-He is.
-He's using pork neck.

753
00:29:02,440 --> 00:29:05,343
-Pork neck skewers.
-Grilled pork neck is fantastic.

754
00:29:05,410 --> 00:29:06,878
Ten minutes left.

755
00:29:06,945 --> 00:29:08,046
ALREADY?

756
00:29:08,947 --> 00:29:09,781
Butter.

757
00:29:10,348 --> 00:29:11,382
STARCH

758
00:29:11,449 --> 00:29:12,917
Nam-no uses pork shoulder.

759
00:29:12,984 --> 00:29:15,487
We often grill pork shoulder as is,

760
00:29:15,553 --> 00:29:17,756
but he now can't use high heat
because of the butter.

761
00:29:18,323 --> 00:29:19,824
ANXIOUS

762
00:29:19,891 --> 00:29:23,228
You're cooking pork,
so it needs to be cooked thoroughly.

763
00:29:23,294 --> 00:29:24,696
-I don't know what he's up to.
-No?

764
00:29:24,763 --> 00:29:27,432
-Why are you using butter?
-Sorry?

765
00:29:27,499 --> 00:29:29,234
He can't cook without butter.

766
00:29:29,300 --> 00:29:30,735
SPOTS A CHANCE TO ATTACK

767
00:29:30,802 --> 00:29:32,871
-He can't?
-He cooks everything in butter.

768
00:29:33,438 --> 00:29:34,939
A DISSING HIT

769
00:29:35,006 --> 00:29:38,176
-He says Nam-no can't cook without butter.
-He always cooks with butter.

770
00:29:38,243 --> 00:29:42,280
He put cooking wine in a spray
and sprays the pork as he cooks.

771
00:29:42,347 --> 00:29:46,050
-He's smothering it with chili oil.
-The skewers.

772
00:29:46,618 --> 00:29:48,086
AND SOME SALT

773
00:29:48,153 --> 00:29:49,220
It looks good.

774
00:29:49,287 --> 00:29:50,421
It's burning.

775
00:29:51,189 --> 00:29:54,692
-It looks rather charred.
-It almost looks burnt.

776
00:29:54,759 --> 00:29:58,029
It's fine with beef,
but when you broil pork,

777
00:29:58,096 --> 00:29:59,531
the fire will keep rising up.

778
00:29:59,597 --> 00:30:01,332
So you have to keep moving it around.

779
00:30:01,399 --> 00:30:04,636
If you don't,
it'll end up charred and burned.

780
00:30:04,702 --> 00:30:06,237
You can't let it get charred.

781
00:30:06,304 --> 00:30:08,640
In this case, the outside chars,
while the inside is uncooked.

782
00:30:08,706 --> 00:30:10,508
-Really?
-But this is pork!

783
00:30:10,575 --> 00:30:13,311
It sounds like trouble.
Is it because it's high in fat?

784
00:30:13,378 --> 00:30:15,847
You have 8 minutes and 30 seconds left.

785
00:30:15,914 --> 00:30:17,315
Wait, I don't have enough time.

786
00:30:17,382 --> 00:30:20,051
Isn't it better to cook it in a pan
and finish it off over fire?

787
00:30:20,618 --> 00:30:22,053
AND HE GRABS A PAN?

788
00:30:22,120 --> 00:30:23,254
He's listening to Poong.

789
00:30:23,321 --> 00:30:25,657
-I knew it!
-No, I just set it aside.

790
00:30:25,723 --> 00:30:28,493
-The pieces on the ends are not cooked.
-They're still raw.

791
00:30:28,560 --> 00:30:29,661
Right?

792
00:30:29,727 --> 00:30:33,598
It must be quite troublesome
to cook those thoroughly.

793
00:30:34,165 --> 00:30:36,401
MICROWAVES INSTANT RICE FIRST

794
00:30:36,467 --> 00:30:37,669
BEFORE MAKING PORK SHOULDER SAUCE

795
00:30:38,236 --> 00:30:39,437
MEAT SOY SAUCE AND DOENJANG

796
00:30:39,504 --> 00:30:41,539
COOKING WINE, SUGAR, MINCED GARLIC

797
00:30:41,606 --> 00:30:42,607
DEEP-FRIED POLLACK SAUCE

798
00:30:43,441 --> 00:30:45,310
Onion.

799
00:30:45,376 --> 00:30:47,111
PORK SHOULDER SAUCE, FINISHED

800
00:30:47,679 --> 00:30:48,646
CHECKS ON THE MEAT

801
00:30:49,214 --> 00:30:51,416
GOLDEN BROWN

802
00:30:51,482 --> 00:30:52,550
They look delicious.

803
00:30:54,152 --> 00:30:56,521
What sauce are you throwing in, Nam-no?

804
00:30:56,588 --> 00:30:58,189
Doenjang and garlic <i>galbi</i> sauce.

805
00:30:58,256 --> 00:30:59,958
-<i>Doenjang </i>and garlic.
-<i>Doenjang</i> and garlic <i>galbi </i>sauce.

806
00:31:00,024 --> 00:31:01,593
-<i>Doenjang </i>and garlic.
-<i>Doenjang</i> and garlic?

807
00:31:01,659 --> 00:31:03,795
Another great performance by Nam-no.

808
00:31:03,862 --> 00:31:06,297
He puts on a flashy show.

809
00:31:06,364 --> 00:31:07,699
THE CALM PIGGY KWON ALSO MAKES SAUCE

810
00:31:08,266 --> 00:31:09,901
5. MIX ONION,
COOKING WINE, CILANTRO, AND MORE

811
00:31:09,968 --> 00:31:12,370
-He's making cilantro salad.
-Cilantro salad!

812
00:31:12,437 --> 00:31:14,539
There are
lots of cilantro lovers these days,

813
00:31:14,606 --> 00:31:16,674
so some places sell
seasoned cilantro salad.

814
00:31:16,741 --> 00:31:18,743
It's cilantro,
one of Hyun-jin's favorites.

815
00:31:19,878 --> 00:31:21,779
The noodles are ready,
so Nam-no strains them.

816
00:31:21,846 --> 00:31:23,915
-It looks hot!
-It's hot.

817
00:31:23,982 --> 00:31:25,950
STEAMING HOT

818
00:31:26,017 --> 00:31:30,021
-But he can hold out for Hyun-jin!
-It must be hot barehanded.

819
00:31:30,088 --> 00:31:32,957
Nam-no fights the heat
to cool the noodles,

820
00:31:33,024 --> 00:31:36,327
whereas Sung-jun mixes cilantro at ease.

821
00:31:36,394 --> 00:31:38,396
FRAMING HIM

822
00:31:38,463 --> 00:31:41,165
-He can't mash the cilantro.
-Sung-jun is his target today.

823
00:31:41,733 --> 00:31:44,168
I'M JUST HAPPY TO COOK FOR HYUN-JIN

824
00:31:44,235 --> 00:31:45,703
What's that sauce?

825
00:31:45,770 --> 00:31:47,472
Peanut sauce and oyster sauce.

826
00:31:47,538 --> 00:31:49,040
It's for dipping the meat.

827
00:31:49,107 --> 00:31:50,742
-It looks good.
-Peanut sauce, oyster sauce, lemon.

828
00:31:50,808 --> 00:31:52,677
It's like Southeast Asian cuisine.

829
00:31:52,744 --> 00:31:56,314
It must taste something like
the Vietnamese spring roll dip.

830
00:31:56,381 --> 00:31:57,749
THE SKEWER SAUCE IS READY

831
00:31:57,815 --> 00:31:59,784
You have under seven minutes left.

832
00:31:59,851 --> 00:32:02,086
That one looks good.

833
00:32:02,153 --> 00:32:04,756
He's making pork <i>galbi</i>
grilled down in sauce.

834
00:32:05,757 --> 00:32:06,658
YUM

835
00:32:06,724 --> 00:32:08,092
It's good!

836
00:32:09,661 --> 00:32:10,695
FIZZ!

837
00:32:10,762 --> 00:32:12,730
Cola?

838
00:32:12,797 --> 00:32:14,499
-Cola?
-<i>Doenjang </i>goes nicely with cola.

839
00:32:14,565 --> 00:32:17,969
-But isn't that zero-sugar cola?
-Does cola go well with that?

840
00:32:18,036 --> 00:32:19,304
-It is.
-It's zero-sugar.

841
00:32:19,370 --> 00:32:23,741
The sweetener used to make that
isn't actual sugar.

842
00:32:23,808 --> 00:32:25,677
That's why I'm adding sugar.

843
00:32:26,244 --> 00:32:27,312
THE BREAKING BALL WITH SUGAR

844
00:32:27,378 --> 00:32:28,680
He modifies it right away.

845
00:32:28,746 --> 00:32:30,848
2ND PLACE FEELS PROUD

846
00:32:30,915 --> 00:32:33,384
-It was a performance.
-It adds flavor!

847
00:32:33,451 --> 00:32:37,088
Poong's advice
usually doesn't end too well.

848
00:32:37,155 --> 00:32:38,456
I know he's second place,

849
00:32:38,523 --> 00:32:40,825
-but he has 15 losses.
-That's a lot.

850
00:32:40,892 --> 00:32:43,795
I still have lots of wins!

851
00:32:44,362 --> 00:32:45,797
7. PUT PERILLA OIL AND TOFU IN THE SOUP

852
00:32:45,863 --> 00:32:46,764
I forgot to chop the tofu.

853
00:32:46,831 --> 00:32:49,600
-Tofu.
-He must make delicious <i>jeotguk-jjigae.</i>

854
00:32:49,667 --> 00:32:50,935
He needs to put in some work.

855
00:32:51,002 --> 00:32:54,605
Chef Sung-jun isn't as witty as usual.

856
00:32:54,672 --> 00:32:56,741
He doesn't even chant, "It looks good!"

857
00:32:56,808 --> 00:32:59,210
He's only focused on cooking.

858
00:32:59,277 --> 00:33:01,112
He knows how important this is.

859
00:33:01,179 --> 00:33:03,214
He's cooking quietly today.

860
00:33:03,281 --> 00:33:05,516
Well, Chef Hyun-jin…

861
00:33:05,583 --> 00:33:07,552
No, I mean, Hyun-jin.

862
00:33:07,618 --> 00:33:10,421
-"Chef Hyun-jin"?
-Who's Chef Hyun-jin?

863
00:33:10,488 --> 00:33:12,123
Hyun-jin, by any chance,

864
00:33:12,190 --> 00:33:14,792
do you eat pork neck medium?

865
00:33:14,859 --> 00:33:17,261
-I've never had it like that.
-Never?

866
00:33:17,328 --> 00:33:19,163
-It's not cooked.
-Medium pork is delicious.

867
00:33:19,731 --> 00:33:20,832
BUILDING UP

868
00:33:20,898 --> 00:33:23,334
-It has to be cooked.
-It has to be.

869
00:33:23,401 --> 00:33:25,370
-Sung-ju! Please report from the field.
-Yes?

870
00:33:25,436 --> 00:33:28,306
Yes, let me run out there.
They have five minutes left!

871
00:33:28,873 --> 00:33:29,974
5 MINUTES?

872
00:33:30,041 --> 00:33:31,042
-Oh, no!
-Five minutes!

873
00:33:31,743 --> 00:33:32,844
REMOVES THE SKEWERS

874
00:33:32,910 --> 00:33:34,579
Why did you pull out the skewers?

875
00:33:34,645 --> 00:33:35,913
He pulled out the skewers!

876
00:33:35,980 --> 00:33:38,316
CHANGING THE STRATEGY
IN THE BOTTOM OF THE 9TH INNING

877
00:33:39,150 --> 00:33:40,651
That's just regular grilled pork neck!

878
00:33:40,718 --> 00:33:43,988
-Weren't you making skewers?
-That's just grilled pork neck!

879
00:33:44,055 --> 00:33:46,257
Will you skewer them back later?

880
00:33:46,324 --> 00:33:47,558
Yes, I will.

881
00:33:47,625 --> 00:33:49,794
Yes, he can always do that.

882
00:33:49,861 --> 00:33:51,162
It's Sung-jun's recipe.

883
00:33:51,229 --> 00:33:52,930
-It's my family's.
-His family's recipe.

884
00:33:52,997 --> 00:33:55,500
-Sung-ju!
-This was quite unexpected.

885
00:33:55,566 --> 00:33:57,168
-The <i>jeotguk-jjigae.</i>
-<i>Jeotguk-jjigae?</i>

886
00:33:57,235 --> 00:33:59,737
-I'm dying to know what it's like.
-It's the biggest factor.

887
00:33:59,804 --> 00:34:02,840
Let me try the soup
4 minutes and 13 seconds before it's over.

888
00:34:02,907 --> 00:34:04,075
His family's recipe.

889
00:34:04,142 --> 00:34:06,177
Can he continue his family's legacy?

890
00:34:06,244 --> 00:34:08,579
WILL HE PASS ON HIS FAMILY'S LEGACY?

891
00:34:08,646 --> 00:34:09,914
It looks good.

892
00:34:10,481 --> 00:34:12,183
-My gosh.
-What's it like?

893
00:34:12,250 --> 00:34:13,818
It's a bit bland for my taste.

894
00:34:13,885 --> 00:34:15,153
IT'S STILL BLAND

895
00:34:15,219 --> 00:34:17,822
-It needs to boil longer.
-Doesn't it need more flavor?

896
00:34:17,889 --> 00:34:20,792
-A bit more.
-It needs more umami.

897
00:34:21,359 --> 00:34:23,294
5. MIX NOODLES WITH SEAWEED FLAKES,

898
00:34:23,361 --> 00:34:26,531
DEEP-FRIED HALF-DRIED POLLACK SAUCE,

899
00:34:26,597 --> 00:34:29,534
SUGAR, OLIVE OIL, AND GEJANG MEAT

900
00:34:29,600 --> 00:34:31,569
-<i>Gejang?</i>
-That looks so good.

901
00:34:31,636 --> 00:34:32,837
Doesn't it look good?

902
00:34:32,904 --> 00:34:34,172
Don't you think I'll win?

903
00:34:35,373 --> 00:34:38,042
Let me try this sauce.

904
00:34:38,109 --> 00:34:40,178
This is Nam-no's pork shoulder sauce.

905
00:34:40,244 --> 00:34:43,648
Can he take his fourth win
against Sung-jun with that?

906
00:34:43,714 --> 00:34:45,249
HIGH EXPECTATIONS

907
00:34:45,883 --> 00:34:47,618
Goodness.

908
00:34:47,685 --> 00:34:50,154
-This is too sour.
-Sour?

909
00:34:50,221 --> 00:34:51,522
Sour? Why is it sour?

910
00:34:51,589 --> 00:34:53,691
-Sour? Why is it sour?
-I have no idea.

911
00:34:53,758 --> 00:34:55,059
It's too sour.

912
00:34:55,126 --> 00:34:57,161
SUDDENLY LOOKS SERIOUS

913
00:34:57,228 --> 00:34:58,830
That's pretty iffy.

914
00:34:58,896 --> 00:34:59,897
-It's unfamiliar.
-Unfamiliar?

915
00:34:59,964 --> 00:35:02,600
-It's the sauce.
-Why is that so?

916
00:35:02,667 --> 00:35:03,568
It's not sour.

917
00:35:03,634 --> 00:35:06,337
Why does it taste sour to me?

918
00:35:06,404 --> 00:35:09,173
If you want to broil pork,
cook it in a pan first, like Nam-no.

919
00:35:09,240 --> 00:35:10,708
Yes, that's the way to do it.

920
00:35:10,775 --> 00:35:12,143
HE DOES IT BACKWARD…

921
00:35:12,710 --> 00:35:14,212
8. STIR-FRY PORK NECK
WITH GOCHUJANG AND CHILI OIL

922
00:35:15,213 --> 00:35:16,647
CHECKS THE TIME AGAIN

923
00:35:17,215 --> 00:35:18,749
ADDING WATER TO THE PAN?

924
00:35:18,816 --> 00:35:19,650
Wait!

925
00:35:19,717 --> 00:35:22,086
-He poured water into the pan too! What?
-What's he doing?

926
00:35:22,153 --> 00:35:24,021
Is he braising the meat?

927
00:35:24,088 --> 00:35:26,390
-You were supposed to make skewers!
-What is this?

928
00:35:26,457 --> 00:35:28,726
-I have a good reason.
-He has a good reason!

929
00:35:28,793 --> 00:35:29,861
It's not cooked yet.

930
00:35:29,927 --> 00:35:33,898
The outside keeps burning,
so he added water to cook it longer.

931
00:35:34,465 --> 00:35:35,633
CHECKING THE TIME YET AGAIN

932
00:35:35,700 --> 00:35:38,603
-His "skewers" turned out kind of weird.
-He'll skewer them now.

933
00:35:38,669 --> 00:35:41,038
Will he skewer them again?
Two minutes and twenty seconds.

934
00:35:41,105 --> 00:35:42,573
But it's too hot.

935
00:35:42,640 --> 00:35:44,675
-You'll skewer them back?
-He puts gloves on.

936
00:35:44,742 --> 00:35:46,611
Sung-jun puts gloves on.

937
00:35:46,677 --> 00:35:48,613
Will he serve skewers just as he promised?

938
00:35:48,679 --> 00:35:52,083
-That's hot.
-It looks hot!

939
00:35:52,150 --> 00:35:54,619
-It looks very hot right now!
-He's doing it.

940
00:35:54,685 --> 00:35:55,953
-It must be hot.
-This is nothing

941
00:35:56,020 --> 00:35:57,688
compared to Hyun-jin's pain.

942
00:35:57,755 --> 00:35:59,724
He's doing this for Hyun-jin!

943
00:35:59,790 --> 00:36:01,893
It's for Hyun-jin on the mound!

944
00:36:01,959 --> 00:36:03,561
I'M HAPPY EVEN WHEN IT BURNS

945
00:36:03,628 --> 00:36:04,529
It's hot!

946
00:36:04,595 --> 00:36:08,599
-He wants to return the happiness to him.
-It must be hot!

947
00:36:08,666 --> 00:36:11,035
-Number 99.
-Number 99.

948
00:36:11,102 --> 00:36:13,037
He had green onions before,
but not anymore.

949
00:36:13,104 --> 00:36:14,805
GREEN ONIONS, TWO OUTS

950
00:36:14,872 --> 00:36:17,341
The green onions on the skewers are gone.

951
00:36:17,408 --> 00:36:18,543
RETURNS WITHOUT GREEN ONION

952
00:36:18,609 --> 00:36:20,178
The skewers look so good!

953
00:36:20,244 --> 00:36:21,078
They look amazing!

954
00:36:21,145 --> 00:36:22,513
THE MEDIA MANIPULATION BEGINS

955
00:36:22,580 --> 00:36:24,315
Look at the skewers!

956
00:36:24,382 --> 00:36:26,851
-He's doing it again.
-These look amazing.

957
00:36:26,918 --> 00:36:29,387
-A minute and 30 seconds.
-A minute and 30 seconds.

958
00:36:29,453 --> 00:36:31,856
He's now making noodles.

959
00:36:31,923 --> 00:36:34,192
Don't you need more sauce?

960
00:36:34,258 --> 00:36:36,227
It's intentional.
I have to serve it with broth.

961
00:36:36,294 --> 00:36:38,196
-This broth.
-Yes, you had that broth.

962
00:36:38,262 --> 00:36:40,731
-<i>Gejang</i>, right?
-He seasoned it with <i>gejang.</i>

963
00:36:40,798 --> 00:36:42,900
He's going to pour the soup here.

964
00:36:42,967 --> 00:36:45,069
I'm serving it with oyster salad too.

965
00:36:45,136 --> 00:36:47,371
<i>Gejang </i>and oyster?

966
00:36:47,438 --> 00:36:49,674
Let me try the soup
for the <i>gejang </i>noodles!

967
00:36:50,808 --> 00:36:53,611
Does it taste good enough
for him to go to the championship?

968
00:36:53,678 --> 00:36:55,813
My goodness!

969
00:36:55,880 --> 00:36:57,281
It's quite iffy.

970
00:36:59,183 --> 00:37:01,385
THIS ONE'S IFFY TOO?

971
00:37:01,452 --> 00:37:03,955
-It's just <i>naengmyeon </i>broth.
-No way.

972
00:37:04,021 --> 00:37:06,691
-Tastes like ordinary <i>naengmyeon</i> broth.
-Fifty seconds.

973
00:37:06,757 --> 00:37:08,859
You have 47 seconds left.

974
00:37:08,926 --> 00:37:11,596
Things still seem unsure.
I don't know who'll make it.

975
00:37:11,662 --> 00:37:14,632
He skewered the meat back.

976
00:37:14,699 --> 00:37:15,866
The skewers look great!

977
00:37:15,933 --> 00:37:18,035
-They're good?
-Sung-jun finishes the skewer.

978
00:37:18,102 --> 00:37:19,070
Where's the green onion?

979
00:37:19,136 --> 00:37:20,838
-It was just for aroma.
-Thirty seconds!

980
00:37:20,905 --> 00:37:22,607
Just to add the aroma?

981
00:37:22,673 --> 00:37:23,774
Thirty-five seconds.

982
00:37:23,841 --> 00:37:25,443
Thirty-five seconds.

983
00:37:25,509 --> 00:37:29,680
This time, Nam-no begins to chop
the seasoned <i>galbi.</i>

984
00:37:29,747 --> 00:37:32,650
I'm not sure how the sauce will taste.

985
00:37:32,717 --> 00:37:34,452
-Fifteen seconds.
-Fifteen seconds.

986
00:37:34,518 --> 00:37:36,854
-Fifteen seconds. Please wrap up!
-Hit the bell first.

987
00:37:36,921 --> 00:37:38,589
-Ten seconds. Ten.
-No!

988
00:37:38,656 --> 00:37:40,358
-What is it?
-Nine. Eight.

989
00:37:40,424 --> 00:37:42,893
-The rice!
-Seven. Six.

990
00:37:42,960 --> 00:37:44,795
It won't be done in seven seconds.

991
00:37:44,862 --> 00:37:46,097
Fifteen seconds. Please wrap up!

992
00:37:46,163 --> 00:37:48,532
NAM-NO HAD ALREADY WARMED THE RICE

993
00:37:48,599 --> 00:37:50,301
Ten. Nine.

994
00:37:50,368 --> 00:37:52,436
Eight. Seven.

995
00:37:52,503 --> 00:37:54,405
-Rice!
-Six. Five.

996
00:37:54,472 --> 00:37:56,474
-Four. Three.
-Four. Three.

997
00:37:56,540 --> 00:37:58,376
-Two. One.
-Two. One.

998
00:37:58,442 --> 00:38:00,911
Hurry up and finish!

999
00:38:00,978 --> 00:38:02,613
Nam-no is done.

1000
00:38:02,680 --> 00:38:03,681
-Sung-jun.
-You forgot the rice?

1001
00:38:03,748 --> 00:38:05,349
-No, I warmed it.
-Did you?

1002
00:38:05,416 --> 00:38:08,185
-Time's up, so take the rice back out.
-Take it out!

1003
00:38:08,252 --> 00:38:09,520
-This is too hot, so one second.
-It's still hot?

1004
00:38:09,820 --> 00:38:11,389
STALLING FOR TIME

1005
00:38:11,455 --> 00:38:13,524
-He must stall for time.
-Where's the lid?

1006
00:38:13,591 --> 00:38:15,092
He needs two more minutes.

1007
00:38:15,159 --> 00:38:17,728
-It's right here.
-He forgot to microwave the rice.

1008
00:38:17,795 --> 00:38:20,531
-The trivet.
-The trivet.

1009
00:38:20,598 --> 00:38:23,734
You finished those,
so we'll let you serve them.

1010
00:38:23,801 --> 00:38:27,204
-I've never seen you so flustered.
-Yes, right.

1011
00:38:27,271 --> 00:38:29,407
He was the former winner
of <i>Culinary Class Wars.</i>

1012
00:38:30,207 --> 00:38:33,044
STALLS 14 SECONDS
AS HE MOVES THE JEOTGUK-JJIGAE

1013
00:38:33,611 --> 00:38:35,279
-Is that okay?
-It smells good.

1014
00:38:35,346 --> 00:38:37,248
WARMED FOR JUST 37 SECONDS,
INSTEAD OF 2 MINUTES

1015
00:38:37,581 --> 00:38:38,983
TOSS

1016
00:38:39,050 --> 00:38:41,719
Ring the bell. He's done.

1017
00:38:41,786 --> 00:38:42,820
Sung-jun is done.

1018
00:38:42,887 --> 00:38:44,322
They really only get 15 minutes.

1019
00:38:44,388 --> 00:38:47,325
The rice. He forgot the rice.

1020
00:38:47,391 --> 00:38:48,926
I'm exhausted.

1021
00:38:48,993 --> 00:38:51,062
He doesn't eat much rice, so…

1022
00:38:51,128 --> 00:38:53,097
-Right, I don't need lots of rice.
-Good.

1023
00:38:53,164 --> 00:38:55,399
Why were you so serious today?

1024
00:38:55,466 --> 00:38:56,901
No, I had fun.

1025
00:38:56,967 --> 00:38:59,003
As expected from a round
between 7th and 8th.

1026
00:39:00,838 --> 00:39:03,708
The quality of the competition
between the 7th and 8th.

1027
00:39:03,774 --> 00:39:08,579
And now, both pork dishes were made
just for Hyun-jin.

1028
00:39:08,646 --> 00:39:11,816
I know I've watched the show on TV,

1029
00:39:11,882 --> 00:39:14,485
but after about five to seven minutes,

1030
00:39:14,552 --> 00:39:17,455
<i>I wasn't so sure</i>
<i>if both dishes would be finished.</i>

1031
00:39:17,521 --> 00:39:19,757
But by the end, these came out nicely.

1032
00:39:19,824 --> 00:39:22,827
-They're both amazing.
-It's such a wonder.

1033
00:39:22,893 --> 00:39:25,096
Chef Nam-no finished first,

1034
00:39:25,162 --> 00:39:27,098
so try Sung-jun, Stop Pigging Out first.

1035
00:39:27,665 --> 00:39:29,967
GEJANG NOODLES WITH OYSTER SALAD

1036
00:39:31,369 --> 00:39:33,471
DOENJANG AND GARLIC PORK GALBI
MADE WITH PORK SHOULDER

1037
00:39:33,537 --> 00:39:34,372
AND CILANTRO

1038
00:39:35,573 --> 00:39:38,409
CHEF YOON NAM-NO'S
SUNG-JUN, STOP PIGGING OUT

1039
00:39:38,476 --> 00:39:40,845
-Should I eat it with cilantro?
-That sounds great.

1040
00:39:40,911 --> 00:39:42,880
That would be wonderful.

1041
00:39:42,947 --> 00:39:44,515
He loves cilantro.

1042
00:39:45,149 --> 00:39:47,618
-You said it was sour.
-The sauce was a bit sour.

1043
00:39:47,685 --> 00:39:49,854
-Nothing in there is sour.
-Really?

1044
00:39:49,920 --> 00:39:52,022
Maybe it has gone bad.

1045
00:39:52,089 --> 00:39:53,557
PFFT

1046
00:39:53,624 --> 00:39:55,993
TRYING TO DISCIPLINE HIM

1047
00:39:56,060 --> 00:39:57,595
WARNING

1048
00:39:57,661 --> 00:39:59,263
<i>Doenjang </i>and garlic sauce, right?

1049
00:39:59,330 --> 00:40:00,464
WHAT'S IT LIKE?

1050
00:40:00,531 --> 00:40:01,465
Yes.

1051
00:40:01,532 --> 00:40:03,667
It's cooked deliciously well.

1052
00:40:03,734 --> 00:40:05,669
-It's cooked well.
-Also,

1053
00:40:05,736 --> 00:40:10,875
I don't usually eat <i>galbi</i>
with garlic or other condiments,

1054
00:40:10,941 --> 00:40:12,977
but I like this one.

1055
00:40:13,043 --> 00:40:14,245
Does it taste sour?

1056
00:40:14,311 --> 00:40:16,213
-Not at all.
-What?

1057
00:40:16,280 --> 00:40:17,915
-Something's odd.
-What is it?

1058
00:40:17,982 --> 00:40:20,951
-We can't trust you anymore.
-This isn't good.

1059
00:40:21,018 --> 00:40:22,653
Go see a doctor.

1060
00:40:22,720 --> 00:40:27,892
But I've always had
an accurate sense of taste.

1061
00:40:27,958 --> 00:40:30,461
-You're at that age now.
-I'm not.

1062
00:40:30,528 --> 00:40:31,796
It's male menopause.

1063
00:40:31,862 --> 00:40:33,831
Something tasted sour. I mean it.

1064
00:40:33,898 --> 00:40:35,366
-He's making a wrap this time.
-A wrap.

1065
00:40:35,433 --> 00:40:36,734
Try adding some oyster salad in it.

1066
00:40:36,801 --> 00:40:41,472
-That's his favorite side dish.
-It has to taste good.

1067
00:40:41,539 --> 00:40:43,441
-He makes it into a wrap.
-It looks good.

1068
00:40:43,507 --> 00:40:46,444
-And the oyster salad.
-The oyster salad.

1069
00:40:46,510 --> 00:40:48,746
-And he…
-Just like that?

1070
00:40:48,813 --> 00:40:51,649
-He eats so deliciously.
-He's enjoying the dish.

1071
00:40:53,083 --> 00:40:53,918
Your mouth

1072
00:40:54,485 --> 00:40:55,886
doesn't seem big on the inside.

1073
00:40:58,622 --> 00:41:00,558
He took a huge bite, but…

1074
00:41:00,624 --> 00:41:02,326
The actual space is tiny.

1075
00:41:02,393 --> 00:41:03,627
It didn't seem big.

1076
00:41:03,694 --> 00:41:05,396
-I have a tiny mouth.
-You were right.

1077
00:41:05,463 --> 00:41:08,065
It's utilized by something else.

1078
00:41:08,132 --> 00:41:10,534
The balance is pretty nice.

1079
00:41:10,601 --> 00:41:13,804
-But this is something I've had.
-Right.

1080
00:41:14,371 --> 00:41:15,573
FACES DANGER

1081
00:41:15,639 --> 00:41:18,309
-He tried to use the oyster salad.
-That's something he always eats.

1082
00:41:18,375 --> 00:41:19,343
It sounds like a crisis.

1083
00:41:19,410 --> 00:41:21,011
-And mix it.
-Mix everything.

1084
00:41:21,078 --> 00:41:24,081
You should give it a good sip
and wet your throat first.

1085
00:41:24,148 --> 00:41:25,883
-"Wet his throat"?
-Wet?

1086
00:41:25,950 --> 00:41:28,919
-Add moisture.
-It's like skincare.

1087
00:41:28,986 --> 00:41:30,554
Did he feel dry to you?

1088
00:41:30,621 --> 00:41:32,523
-Wet his throat first.
-Wetting.

1089
00:41:32,590 --> 00:41:33,757
-Can he mix everything?
-Yes.

1090
00:41:33,824 --> 00:41:36,026
-Everything?
-Mix everything.

1091
00:41:36,093 --> 00:41:40,030
<i>-You added </i>gejang <i>in chili sauce, right?</i>
<i>-I did.</i>

1092
00:41:40,097 --> 00:41:41,866
But it wasn't quite enough.

1093
00:41:41,932 --> 00:41:42,967
SLURP

1094
00:41:43,033 --> 00:41:45,903
-My gosh. It looks good.
-He makes it look so good.

1095
00:41:45,970 --> 00:41:48,839
The oyster salad
already seemed so delicious.

1096
00:41:48,906 --> 00:41:51,342
-He glares at him.
-Was it good?

1097
00:41:51,408 --> 00:41:53,544
It must've been good. The delicious glare.

1098
00:41:53,611 --> 00:41:55,679
-What did he mean by that?
-What is it?

1099
00:41:55,746 --> 00:41:57,781
I think the cold broth…

1100
00:41:57,848 --> 00:41:58,949
It…

1101
00:41:59,016 --> 00:42:00,417
kills the flavors a little.

1102
00:42:00,484 --> 00:42:02,786
-It doesn't help.
-Too much noodles.

1103
00:42:02,853 --> 00:42:05,022
-If it were just <i>gejang…</i>
-I shouldn't have made the broth.

1104
00:42:05,089 --> 00:42:07,057
-Did it turn bland?
-Yes, if it were just mixed…

1105
00:42:07,124 --> 00:42:11,562
-At times, too much can backfire.
-It tasted only like <i>naengmyeon </i>broth.

1106
00:42:11,629 --> 00:42:13,297
-Why don't you try it with rice?
-Sure.

1107
00:42:13,364 --> 00:42:16,667
This is the good part.

1108
00:42:16,734 --> 00:42:19,270
Hyun-jin with a small appetite.

1109
00:42:21,739 --> 00:42:23,641
-This is worth ten points.
-Ten points.

1110
00:42:23,707 --> 00:42:25,843
HAPPY, MISERABLE

1111
00:42:25,910 --> 00:42:27,811
Lastly, try the noodles
and the meat together.

1112
00:42:27,878 --> 00:42:29,980
-The noodles and the meat.
-Noodles and meat.

1113
00:42:30,047 --> 00:42:32,850
-The cold noodles.
-This may have a different taste.

1114
00:42:32,917 --> 00:42:33,751
The barbecue joint style.

1115
00:42:34,318 --> 00:42:36,120
AT ONE BITE!

1116
00:42:36,186 --> 00:42:38,489
The noodles and <i>gejang</i>.

1117
00:42:38,989 --> 00:42:40,925
He definitely doesn't eat just a bit.

1118
00:42:40,991 --> 00:42:42,226
He eats so well.

1119
00:42:44,061 --> 00:42:45,262
GLANCES

1120
00:42:45,329 --> 00:42:47,765
HIS FACE ALREADY SAYS IT ALL…

1121
00:42:48,332 --> 00:42:50,167
FEELS ANXIOUS AGAIN

1122
00:42:50,234 --> 00:42:52,970
I just want to eat this side.

1123
00:42:53,604 --> 00:42:55,339
-Oh, no.
-The <i>gejang </i>noodles…

1124
00:42:55,406 --> 00:42:57,508
DIVIDED BETWEEN JOY AND SORROW

1125
00:42:57,575 --> 00:42:59,510
-He drew the line.
-He should've stopped.

1126
00:42:59,577 --> 00:43:02,713
It was because Sung-jun said
Hyun-jin had to have soup.

1127
00:43:02,780 --> 00:43:04,481
It was a last-minute addition.

1128
00:43:04,548 --> 00:43:06,684
-Wait, you.
-That was a shame.

1129
00:43:06,750 --> 00:43:09,687
-The <i>jeotguk</i> might be good.
-Yes, I agree.

1130
00:43:09,753 --> 00:43:12,256
Next, Chef Sung-jun's dish.

1131
00:43:12,323 --> 00:43:13,857
Nam-no Can't Pig Out Like Me.

1132
00:43:13,924 --> 00:43:15,726
JEOTGUK-JJIGAE
MADE WITH HIS FAMILY'S RECIPE

1133
00:43:16,627 --> 00:43:19,830
PORK NECK SKEWERS
SERVED WITH SEASONED CILANTRO

1134
00:43:21,065 --> 00:43:24,802
CHEF KWON SUNG-JUN'S
NAM-NO CAN'T PIG OUT LIKE ME

1135
00:43:25,603 --> 00:43:28,072
-Let me set it up for him.
-Is that so?

1136
00:43:28,138 --> 00:43:30,140
-Do you want to see the rice?
-Yes, let me check.

1137
00:43:30,207 --> 00:43:32,142
AFTER ALL,
HE WARMED IT ONLY FOR 37 SECONDS

1138
00:43:32,209 --> 00:43:33,510
-Are you switching it out?
-No.

1139
00:43:33,577 --> 00:43:34,979
Do you have rice in your pocket?

1140
00:43:35,045 --> 00:43:36,880
-He didn't have enough time.
-The center must be hard.

1141
00:43:36,947 --> 00:43:39,817
-So how's the rice?
-What if he drops it in the soup?

1142
00:43:39,883 --> 00:43:41,952
-Sung-jun?
-It looks good.

1143
00:43:42,019 --> 00:43:42,886
Does it?

1144
00:43:42,953 --> 00:43:44,254
DROP…

1145
00:43:45,456 --> 00:43:47,725
Is that sand? It's like sand!

1146
00:43:47,791 --> 00:43:48,859
INTRIGUED

1147
00:43:48,926 --> 00:43:50,494
-No.
-It's al dente in the middle.

1148
00:43:50,561 --> 00:43:52,630
-It's because…
-Give him just a little.

1149
00:43:52,696 --> 00:43:55,065
It's because he has to eat it

1150
00:43:55,132 --> 00:43:57,201
with the soup
passed down within my family.

1151
00:43:57,267 --> 00:43:58,836
-Wait!
-You can't do that.

1152
00:43:58,902 --> 00:44:00,371
He never mixes rice and soup.

1153
00:44:00,437 --> 00:44:01,305
Right!

1154
00:44:01,372 --> 00:44:04,675
-Why are you trying to jinx him?
-I just saved you.

1155
00:44:04,742 --> 00:44:07,811
He switched the rice bowl
and the soup bowl!

1156
00:44:07,878 --> 00:44:08,746
He was too flustered.

1157
00:44:08,812 --> 00:44:11,081
SOUP BOWL, RICE BOWL?

1158
00:44:11,148 --> 00:44:13,417
-He got flustered.
-The soup bowl and rice bowl are switched.

1159
00:44:13,484 --> 00:44:16,654
-This is crazy.
-You must be really nervous.

1160
00:44:16,720 --> 00:44:19,957
-He was quite worried because of the rice.
-No, no, no.

1161
00:44:20,024 --> 00:44:22,826
Maybe that's what their family does.

1162
00:44:22,893 --> 00:44:25,262
There's a reason for this.

1163
00:44:25,329 --> 00:44:26,363
Let's hear out the reason.

1164
00:44:26,430 --> 00:44:28,866
I just put the soup in the other bowl,

1165
00:44:28,932 --> 00:44:30,968
which means it goes the other way
and will let him win.

1166
00:44:31,902 --> 00:44:32,770
What now?

1167
00:44:32,836 --> 00:44:34,071
You can just taste it now.

1168
00:44:34,138 --> 00:44:35,205
EDIT PLEASE

1169
00:44:35,272 --> 00:44:37,775
-Are those the skewers?
-They are.

1170
00:44:37,841 --> 00:44:41,445
He didn't grill them
the typical way they're grilled.

1171
00:44:42,212 --> 00:44:43,247
It looks good.

1172
00:44:43,313 --> 00:44:45,215
-Over charcoal…
-Stop saying it looks good.

1173
00:44:45,282 --> 00:44:47,317
<i>He broiled them, cooked them in a pan,</i>

1174
00:44:47,384 --> 00:44:49,353
<i>poured water on them,</i>
<i>and broiled them again.</i>

1175
00:44:49,420 --> 00:44:52,756
-It's a double-reversal.
-Try it with the cilantro.

1176
00:44:52,823 --> 00:44:54,825
Pork neck is a tender cut.

1177
00:44:54,892 --> 00:44:56,060
NODS

1178
00:44:56,126 --> 00:44:57,461
He nods.

1179
00:44:57,528 --> 00:44:59,930
-What's he doing next?
-I'll try it with the sauce.

1180
00:44:59,997 --> 00:45:02,232
-The sauce is the kick.
-You didn't last time, so do it.

1181
00:45:02,299 --> 00:45:04,435
-All right. Is the sauce the kick?
-Yes, of course.

1182
00:45:04,501 --> 00:45:05,502
Do I need a lot of sauce?

1183
00:45:06,103 --> 00:45:08,172
-Just a little.
-Right.

1184
00:45:08,238 --> 00:45:10,140
You just said it was the kick.

1185
00:45:10,207 --> 00:45:11,542
You can get a good dip.

1186
00:45:12,876 --> 00:45:13,877
YUM

1187
00:45:13,944 --> 00:45:15,245
I think it's going to be good.

1188
00:45:16,647 --> 00:45:18,315
Pork neck may be a bit greasy.

1189
00:45:18,382 --> 00:45:20,050
That's when you can have the <i>jjigae.</i>

1190
00:45:20,684 --> 00:45:21,685
STRAIGHT TO THE SOUP

1191
00:45:21,752 --> 00:45:24,221
It must've been greasy. Try the soup next.

1192
00:45:24,288 --> 00:45:26,490
-The <i>jeotguk.</i>
-The <i>jeotguk-jjigae.</i>

1193
00:45:31,095 --> 00:45:32,563
The <i>jeotguk-jjigae!</i>

1194
00:45:32,629 --> 00:45:34,465
-It's…
-It's his family's recipe.

1195
00:45:34,531 --> 00:45:35,766
HAHAHA

1196
00:45:35,833 --> 00:45:37,401
Wait, we don't know yet.

1197
00:45:37,468 --> 00:45:39,503
He doesn't know what <i>jeotguk-jjigae </i>is.

1198
00:45:39,570 --> 00:45:40,838
It must be good.

1199
00:45:40,904 --> 00:45:43,540
-Well, it's good.
-Yes?

1200
00:45:43,607 --> 00:45:45,008
But it's a bit

1201
00:45:45,075 --> 00:45:47,444
-too strong in its flavor.
-Right?

1202
00:45:47,511 --> 00:45:49,546
-What happened, Sung-ju?
-Yes, you said it was bland!

1203
00:45:49,613 --> 00:45:53,250
It was bland
when he had four minutes left.

1204
00:45:53,317 --> 00:45:55,552
<i>Jeotguk-jjigae </i>is usually a bit salty.

1205
00:45:55,619 --> 00:45:58,355
-Try it with some tofu.
-My gosh.

1206
00:45:58,422 --> 00:46:00,691
He might need implants soon.

1207
00:46:00,758 --> 00:46:03,694
The instant rice is practically raw.

1208
00:46:03,761 --> 00:46:04,728
It has

1209
00:46:04,795 --> 00:46:07,364
the texture of long grain rice
from South America.

1210
00:46:07,431 --> 00:46:10,167
-Couscous?
-Undercooked rice?

1211
00:46:10,234 --> 00:46:11,435
-No.
-Is it like couscous?

1212
00:46:11,502 --> 00:46:12,703
-No, it's al dente.
-Al dente?

1213
00:46:12,770 --> 00:46:14,304
-It's al dente?
-He's an Italian chef…

1214
00:46:14,371 --> 00:46:16,507
-That's what it tastes like.
-…so he made it to al dente.

1215
00:46:16,573 --> 00:46:18,842
But other than how strong it tastes,

1216
00:46:18,909 --> 00:46:21,478
-it's not so bad.
-<i>Jeotguk-jjigae.</i>

1217
00:46:22,246 --> 00:46:23,847
He really loves cilantro.

1218
00:46:23,914 --> 00:46:25,649
-I do.
-He picks up lots of cilantro.

1219
00:46:25,716 --> 00:46:26,850
I couldn't eat it at first,

1220
00:46:26,917 --> 00:46:30,087
but I began to eat it
after trying a seasoned salad.

1221
00:46:30,154 --> 00:46:31,455
Seasoned cilantro salad?

1222
00:46:32,022 --> 00:46:33,157
A BIG BITE

1223
00:46:33,223 --> 00:46:35,225
-Right?
-The cilantro salad must be good.

1224
00:46:36,460 --> 00:46:37,761
CURIOUS

1225
00:46:37,828 --> 00:46:39,696
The cilantro salad is really good.

1226
00:46:40,798 --> 00:46:42,666
The Eagles fan
throws his fists in the air.

1227
00:46:42,733 --> 00:46:45,302
-I'm starting to see the fall.
-Personally speaking,

1228
00:46:45,369 --> 00:46:47,905
it's much better when the meat
is only served with this.

1229
00:46:49,740 --> 00:46:52,309
-He had a mishap too.
-We don't know how this will go.

1230
00:46:52,376 --> 00:46:54,745
In the end,
it's just the pork that matters.

1231
00:46:54,812 --> 00:46:55,879
He keeps eating it.

1232
00:46:57,414 --> 00:46:59,449
No?

1233
00:46:59,516 --> 00:47:03,687
-It's time to decide.
-Hyun-jin has to pick one now.

1234
00:47:03,754 --> 00:47:06,757
-Press one for Yoon Nam-no.
-Let's go!

1235
00:47:06,824 --> 00:47:08,425
<i>Press two for Kwon Sung-jun.</i>

1236
00:47:09,726 --> 00:47:10,694
<i>Make your decision</i>

1237
00:47:10,761 --> 00:47:12,462
and press the button!

1238
00:47:13,263 --> 00:47:15,766
Who did he choose?

1239
00:47:15,833 --> 00:47:18,468
Who did Hyun-jin choose?

1240
00:47:18,535 --> 00:47:20,737
Let's find out! Show us!

1241
00:47:20,804 --> 00:47:23,974
-It's nerve-racking.
-It's a very important decision.

1242
00:47:24,041 --> 00:47:27,444
-Who'll win?
-Will Sung-jun win against Nam-no

1243
00:47:27,511 --> 00:47:29,947
and be deeply loved by the Eagles' fans?

1244
00:47:30,013 --> 00:47:34,218
Or will Nam-no win against Sung-jun,

1245
00:47:34,284 --> 00:47:38,121
add another win to his neat sweep,

1246
00:47:38,188 --> 00:47:39,690
and win a star?

1247
00:47:39,756 --> 00:47:41,391
Who did Hyun-jin choose?

1248
00:47:41,458 --> 00:47:42,826
Which one is it?

1249
00:47:43,527 --> 00:47:45,462
Will it be Sung-jun or Nam-no?

1250
00:47:45,529 --> 00:47:46,630
YOON NAM-NO WINS

1251
00:47:47,731 --> 00:47:48,665
CHEF YOON NAM-NO WINS

1252
00:47:48,732 --> 00:47:52,035
Yoon Nam-no takes the victory!

1253
00:47:52,102 --> 00:47:54,671
He wins all four rounds against Sung-jun!

1254
00:47:54,738 --> 00:47:56,173
NAM-NO, SUNG-JUN'S WORST ENEMY

1255
00:47:56,240 --> 00:47:57,441
He's Sung-jun's worst enemy.

1256
00:47:57,507 --> 00:47:59,476
-I can't believe this.
-Sung-jun's worst enemy.

1257
00:47:59,543 --> 00:48:03,080
The meat was both delicious.

1258
00:48:03,146 --> 00:48:05,816
<i>This one went very well with rice.</i>

1259
00:48:05,883 --> 00:48:06,783
<i>The pork shoulder?</i>

1260
00:48:06,850 --> 00:48:09,052
<i>But I could eat this without it.</i>

1261
00:48:09,119 --> 00:48:10,821
THE PORK NECK WAS FINE WITHOUT RICE

1262
00:48:10,888 --> 00:48:13,190
He said he always eats a bowl of rice.

1263
00:48:13,257 --> 00:48:14,892
I would've eaten this on a game day.

1264
00:48:14,958 --> 00:48:16,827
-On a game day.
-Even if the rice was the same.

1265
00:48:16,894 --> 00:48:20,564
It means Chef Nam-no takes
his ninth victory.

1266
00:48:21,164 --> 00:48:25,769
Nam-no, Jong-won, and Ho-young
all have nine wins.

1267
00:48:25,836 --> 00:48:27,671
Yes, he's at nine wins.

1268
00:48:27,738 --> 00:48:30,374
And Sung-jun got eliminated.

1269
00:48:30,440 --> 00:48:32,843
How do you feel, Chef Nam-no?

1270
00:48:32,910 --> 00:48:33,977
I really hope

1271
00:48:34,044 --> 00:48:35,812
Eun-yeong loses the next round.

1272
00:48:35,879 --> 00:48:39,049
-You can do it, Eun-yeong!
-He's hopeful.

1273
00:48:39,116 --> 00:48:40,384
Root for me.

1274
00:48:40,450 --> 00:48:42,452
If I make it to the championship,
I'll beat everyone.

1275
00:48:42,519 --> 00:48:44,554
-You never know.
-No.

1276
00:48:44,621 --> 00:48:47,224
Hyun-jin, please put a star on him!

1277
00:48:47,291 --> 00:48:49,760
Nam-no seizes his ninth win!

1278
00:48:49,826 --> 00:48:52,129
-Thank you.
-He ends the season with nine wins.

1279
00:48:52,195 --> 00:48:53,463
Nam-no!

1280
00:48:53,530 --> 00:48:56,099
Sung-jun is wearing
the Eagles uniform underneath.

1281
00:49:00,804 --> 00:49:03,707
Show him. Show him what you're wearing.

1282
00:49:04,508 --> 00:49:05,509
-Oh, no.
-What is it?

1283
00:49:05,575 --> 00:49:06,710
-Show him.
-Your plan.

1284
00:49:06,777 --> 00:49:09,680
-You're a forever Eagles fan.
-What was your celebration?

1285
00:49:09,746 --> 00:49:11,448
-If I had won…
-What would you have done?

1286
00:49:11,515 --> 00:49:13,517
He's an Eagles fan.

1287
00:49:13,583 --> 00:49:14,918
His back looks so sad.

1288
00:49:14,985 --> 00:49:17,120
Sung-jun takes his ninth win!

1289
00:49:17,187 --> 00:49:18,622
-You won.
-Sung-jun!

1290
00:49:18,689 --> 00:49:20,524
TA-DA
RYU HYUN-JIN

1291
00:49:21,792 --> 00:49:23,260
I'M SORRY

1292
00:49:23,827 --> 00:49:24,695
FALLS…

1293
00:49:24,761 --> 00:49:26,663
What a shame, Sung-jun.

1294
00:49:26,730 --> 00:49:28,198
I wanted to do that.

1295
00:49:28,265 --> 00:49:29,466
TATTERED

1296
00:49:29,533 --> 00:49:30,901
Let's move on.

1297
00:49:30,968 --> 00:49:32,035
OKAY, CUT!

1298
00:49:33,403 --> 00:49:35,038
-Thank you for the meal.
-Don't mention it.

1299
00:49:35,105 --> 00:49:36,540
-May I take a picture?
-Of course.

1300
00:49:36,606 --> 00:49:37,975
One, two, three.

1301
00:49:38,041 --> 00:49:39,443
One, two, three.

1302
00:49:40,610 --> 00:49:42,946
I'M HAPPY, EVEN THOUGH I LOST

1303
00:49:43,013 --> 00:49:47,017
<i>The second cook-off played</i>
<i>with ingredients from Hyun-jin's fridge.</i>

1304
00:49:47,084 --> 00:49:49,853
The two monsters of the show are up.

1305
00:49:49,920 --> 00:49:53,256
The Chinese monster, Chef Park Eun-yeong

1306
00:49:53,323 --> 00:49:57,661
versus the bizarre food monster,
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong.

1307
00:49:57,728 --> 00:49:58,795
He's scary.

1308
00:49:58,862 --> 00:50:02,265
Chef Eun-yeong has eight wins,

1309
00:50:02,332 --> 00:50:04,468
and Webtoon Artist Poong has ten wins.

1310
00:50:04,534 --> 00:50:07,304
If Poong wins, Eun-yeong is eliminated,

1311
00:50:07,371 --> 00:50:08,939
-and Nam-no will move on.
-No way.

1312
00:50:09,006 --> 00:50:09,873
Yes!

1313
00:50:09,940 --> 00:50:11,608
If Chef Eun-yeong wins,

1314
00:50:11,675 --> 00:50:13,276
-Nam-no is eliminated.
-Okay.

1315
00:50:13,343 --> 00:50:15,379
-This will decide their fate.
-Please win.

1316
00:50:15,445 --> 00:50:17,280
One of the two will be eliminated.

1317
00:50:17,347 --> 00:50:20,984
I would've taken second place
if I hadn't lost against him four times.

1318
00:50:21,051 --> 00:50:22,252
Nam-no made him second place.

1319
00:50:22,319 --> 00:50:23,754
You're right.

1320
00:50:23,820 --> 00:50:25,555
I hope he wins today

1321
00:50:25,622 --> 00:50:28,025
and lets me move on to the playoffs.

1322
00:50:28,091 --> 00:50:29,192
I'm rooting for him.

1323
00:50:29,259 --> 00:50:31,928
I can't stand to see Chef Nam-no move up.

1324
00:50:33,497 --> 00:50:36,767
I mostly played the role
of Eun-yeong's bully,

1325
00:50:36,833 --> 00:50:38,602
but I must root for her now.

1326
00:50:38,668 --> 00:50:40,504
-Please look forward to it.
-I see.

1327
00:50:40,570 --> 00:50:42,239
"Look forward to it"?

1328
00:50:42,305 --> 00:50:44,875
-They split up.
-They want two different things.

1329
00:50:44,941 --> 00:50:47,744
You're the best, Kim Poong!

1330
00:50:47,811 --> 00:50:49,146
You're the best!

1331
00:50:49,212 --> 00:50:50,580
Kim Poong!

1332
00:50:50,647 --> 00:50:53,250
-You're the best, Kim Poong! Go!
-Let's go!

1333
00:50:53,316 --> 00:50:54,885
THAT'S GREAT

1334
00:50:55,218 --> 00:50:56,620
INVIGORATING FOR ALL

1335
00:50:56,686 --> 00:50:57,621
Please win.

1336
00:50:57,687 --> 00:50:58,955
NAM-NO'S THE BEST

1337
00:50:59,189 --> 00:51:00,057
EMBARRASSED

1338
00:51:00,123 --> 00:51:02,659
-Up against him is…
-He doesn't watch baseball,

1339
00:51:02,726 --> 00:51:04,027
so he doesn't know how it's done.

1340
00:51:04,094 --> 00:51:06,696
-You don't do this here usually.
-We don't.

1341
00:51:06,763 --> 00:51:08,698
We usually don't,

1342
00:51:08,765 --> 00:51:12,002
-but the situation is quite dire.
-Please.

1343
00:51:12,936 --> 00:51:15,105
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S INGREDIENTS:

1344
00:51:15,172 --> 00:51:17,340
MELON, THIN SKIRT, INSIDE SKIRT,
BREAD, RAMYEON, CURRY POWDER

1345
00:51:17,407 --> 00:51:19,309
Here's the name of my dish.

1346
00:51:19,876 --> 00:51:21,745
I'll make deep-fried melon.

1347
00:51:21,812 --> 00:51:24,681
-Deep-fried melon?
-That's incredible!

1348
00:51:24,748 --> 00:51:28,051
-You won, Eun-yeong.
-I just need my dish to turn out normal.

1349
00:51:28,118 --> 00:51:30,554
-It won't be easy.
-Doesn't it have too much water?

1350
00:51:30,620 --> 00:51:31,888
Deep-fried melon?

1351
00:51:31,955 --> 00:51:35,392
Actually, I've deep-fried
just about everything, don't you think?

1352
00:51:35,459 --> 00:51:37,861
I've deep-fried most things,

1353
00:51:37,928 --> 00:51:40,163
and oh, my. He has a melon.

1354
00:51:40,730 --> 00:51:42,265
AMAZED

1355
00:51:42,332 --> 00:51:44,201
Have you ever had deep-fried melon?

1356
00:51:44,267 --> 00:51:47,137
-No, has anyone here had it?
-Exactly.

1357
00:51:47,204 --> 00:51:49,506
-Not even the chefs?
-Not many have had deep-fried melon.

1358
00:51:49,573 --> 00:51:51,608
-We've never even heard of it.
-You can't eat it.

1359
00:51:51,675 --> 00:51:54,711
-I'll serve it with melon sauce.
-Melon sauce?

1360
00:51:54,778 --> 00:51:56,613
That can be a bit boring,

1361
00:51:56,680 --> 00:51:58,248
so I'll also deep-fry some beef

1362
00:51:58,315 --> 00:52:00,851
-and serve two different fries.
-What?

1363
00:52:00,917 --> 00:52:03,453
-You won, Eun-yeong.
-The beef will be the main dish.

1364
00:52:03,520 --> 00:52:06,756
No, the deep-fried melon is the key dish.

1365
00:52:07,691 --> 00:52:09,860
CHEF EUN-YEONG'S INGREDIENTS:
SABLEFISH, PERILLA LEAF

1366
00:52:09,926 --> 00:52:12,095
CHEONGYANG PEPPER, EGG,
SESAME OIL, OYSTER SAUCE, CRUSHED GARLIC

1367
00:52:12,162 --> 00:52:14,798
The name of my dish is as follows.

1368
00:52:14,865 --> 00:52:17,267
Kim Poong, Strikeout!

1369
00:52:17,334 --> 00:52:19,402
Kim Poong, Strikeout!

1370
00:52:20,537 --> 00:52:21,738
AWESOME

1371
00:52:21,805 --> 00:52:23,039
IMPRESSED

1372
00:52:23,607 --> 00:52:26,009
WAS SHE TRYING TO DO THIS?

1373
00:52:26,576 --> 00:52:29,212
HER STRIKEOUT CALL MAKES HIM DIZZY

1374
00:52:29,279 --> 00:52:30,614
What did she do?

1375
00:52:30,947 --> 00:52:32,516
MY HEAD HURTS

1376
00:52:32,582 --> 00:52:34,317
Strikeout. Kim Poong, Strikeout!

1377
00:52:34,384 --> 00:52:35,218
Excellent.

1378
00:52:35,285 --> 00:52:36,186
YOUNGER BRO IS PLEASED

1379
00:52:36,253 --> 00:52:40,657
-This is my third round against Poong.
-Yes.

1380
00:52:40,724 --> 00:52:44,127
And if he loses the third time today,
he will be struck out.

1381
00:52:44,194 --> 00:52:46,863
-I see.
-That's why I named the dish as such.

1382
00:52:46,930 --> 00:52:49,733
Hyun-jin, you said
you liked deep-fried half-dried pollack.

1383
00:52:49,799 --> 00:52:52,669
Then I saw sablefish in your fridge,

1384
00:52:52,736 --> 00:52:54,404
so I'll make delicious deep-fried fish

1385
00:52:54,471 --> 00:52:58,475
and serve it with a mix of two sauces,
Chinese and Korean.

1386
00:52:58,542 --> 00:52:59,876
Also, it'll look like

1387
00:52:59,943 --> 00:53:02,445
a fish that's swimming.

1388
00:53:02,512 --> 00:53:05,549
I hoped you would continue to push ahead

1389
00:53:05,615 --> 00:53:07,817
in full energy, just like that fish.

1390
00:53:07,884 --> 00:53:10,053
So what's your dish called again?

1391
00:53:10,620 --> 00:53:13,023
Kim Poong, Strikeout!

1392
00:53:13,590 --> 00:53:15,792
HER STRIKEOUT CALL
IS ALWAYS FULL OF SPIRIT

1393
00:53:16,760 --> 00:53:18,295
EMBARRASSED LITTLE BRO

1394
00:53:18,361 --> 00:53:21,932
If the ump called a strikeout like that,

1395
00:53:21,998 --> 00:53:23,400
I would be insanely mad.

1396
00:53:23,466 --> 00:53:24,734
OPENLY ANNOYING

1397
00:53:24,801 --> 00:53:27,504
I mean, from the batter's perspective,

1398
00:53:27,571 --> 00:53:30,407
I'd be angrier at her for doing that
than at the pitcher.

1399
00:53:30,473 --> 00:53:32,576
-It calls for a bench-clearing brawl.
-I'd be so mad.

1400
00:53:32,642 --> 00:53:34,077
You're right. So true.

1401
00:53:34,144 --> 00:53:35,412
-He would get mad.
-Totally.

1402
00:53:35,478 --> 00:53:38,648
Their deep-fried dish round will begin.

1403
00:53:38,715 --> 00:53:41,885
A BIG MATCH TO REACH THE CHAMPIONSHIP

1404
00:53:41,952 --> 00:53:43,620
A cooking monster
bred by <i>Chef & My Fridge,</i>

1405
00:53:43,687 --> 00:53:47,557
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong is here
to secure his place as the second.

1406
00:53:47,624 --> 00:53:48,925
It's not just Kim Poong.

1407
00:53:48,992 --> 00:53:51,595
She wants to take Yoon Nam-no down too.

1408
00:53:51,661 --> 00:53:54,097
Chef Park Eun-yeong
is up for the challenge.

1409
00:53:54,164 --> 00:53:58,201
Which one of them will be chosen
by the Korean Monster?

1410
00:53:58,268 --> 00:54:02,038
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1411
00:54:04,407 --> 00:54:06,309
THE MATCH STARTS

1412
00:54:06,376 --> 00:54:07,978
Please win!

1413
00:54:08,044 --> 00:54:09,679
-Go, Eun-yeong!
-Let's go.

1414
00:54:09,746 --> 00:54:11,781
This is an important match.

1415
00:54:11,848 --> 00:54:13,750
THE MATCH WILL DECIDE THE FINAL 5

1416
00:54:13,817 --> 00:54:17,687
-I'm dying to know how he'll fry a melon.
-I wonder.

1417
00:54:17,754 --> 00:54:21,925
-How will he use that melon?
-Deep-frying a melon?

1418
00:54:21,992 --> 00:54:23,360
It's very high in sugar content.

1419
00:54:23,426 --> 00:54:27,397
Well, people deep-fry bananas,
mangoes, and even pineapples.

1420
00:54:27,464 --> 00:54:29,666
-I believe in him.
-You do?

1421
00:54:29,733 --> 00:54:31,835
WHAT ABOUT EUN-YEONG,
WORKING WITH SUNG-JUN'S SUPPORT?

1422
00:54:31,901 --> 00:54:34,070
-Is that sablefish?
-It is.

1423
00:54:34,137 --> 00:54:36,506
She's going to make deep-fried sablefish.

1424
00:54:37,641 --> 00:54:39,809
-She's very skillful.
-You're doing great so far.

1425
00:54:42,412 --> 00:54:43,947
It looks so good.

1426
00:54:44,014 --> 00:54:44,948
CONTINUOUS SUPPORT

1427
00:54:45,015 --> 00:54:47,517
She's trying to deep-fry the sablefish.

1428
00:54:47,584 --> 00:54:49,986
-She cut the pieces of wings first.
-She's frying that whole?

1429
00:54:50,053 --> 00:54:52,889
When she said it'd fly,
she meant that she'd fry it whole.

1430
00:54:52,956 --> 00:54:55,292
-I see.
-She gave the fish wings.

1431
00:54:55,358 --> 00:54:56,660
-These are wings.
-She's doing it

1432
00:54:56,726 --> 00:54:58,795
like she would deep-fry a sea bream.

1433
00:54:58,862 --> 00:55:00,664
Chinese cuisine does that a lot.

1434
00:55:00,730 --> 00:55:02,832
It has tender meat,
so it'll be very delicious.

1435
00:55:02,899 --> 00:55:04,334
-It has tender meat?
-Yes.

1436
00:55:04,401 --> 00:55:07,871
We've often seen deep-fried fish,

1437
00:55:07,937 --> 00:55:11,775
but deep-fried fruit?
And among them, a juicy melon?

1438
00:55:11,841 --> 00:55:13,109
Hmm? Bread?

1439
00:55:13,176 --> 00:55:14,944
-Bread.
-Why is he cutting bread?

1440
00:55:15,011 --> 00:55:17,480
Will he use that instead of batter?

1441
00:55:17,547 --> 00:55:21,518
All he needs to do is make batter
that can endure that kind of moisture.

1442
00:55:21,584 --> 00:55:23,853
-But can Poong make that?
-Right.

1443
00:55:23,920 --> 00:55:25,989
Breadcrumbs might do the trick.

1444
00:55:26,056 --> 00:55:28,692
-As Hyun-suk said, it's about the batter.
-Yes.

1445
00:55:28,758 --> 00:55:31,428
The batter to deep-fry the melon.

1446
00:55:31,494 --> 00:55:33,163
And because they're both deep-frying,

1447
00:55:33,229 --> 00:55:34,931
-moisture is a factor.
-Mix all-purpose flour.

1448
00:55:34,998 --> 00:55:37,267
-Finishing first will also be important.
-Yes.

1449
00:55:37,834 --> 00:55:39,269
BURNING EYES

1450
00:55:39,336 --> 00:55:41,671
Eun-yeong, aren't you too serious?
After all, it's a show.

1451
00:55:41,738 --> 00:55:42,572
No, I'm dead serious.

1452
00:55:42,639 --> 00:55:44,341
-You have to be. And win.
-I'm serious.

1453
00:55:44,407 --> 00:55:46,910
Smile a little, will you?
I'm too scared to talk to you.

1454
00:55:46,976 --> 00:55:48,645
What's Chef Eun-yeong doing?

1455
00:55:48,712 --> 00:55:49,746
Go, Eun-yeong!

1456
00:55:49,813 --> 00:55:50,914
Are you showering the fish?

1457
00:55:50,980 --> 00:55:53,416
-I'm battering it.
-Just don't make a mistake.

1458
00:55:53,483 --> 00:55:55,151
-Is that how you're doing it?
-Yes.

1459
00:55:55,218 --> 00:55:56,953
She's using starch water too.

1460
00:55:57,020 --> 00:56:01,291
-She's using starch water too?
-I thought the meat may be too tender,

1461
00:56:01,358 --> 00:56:03,393
-so I'm battering it twice.
-In case it falls apart?

1462
00:56:03,460 --> 00:56:06,162
-That'll give the fish a nice texture.
-You're doing great!

1463
00:56:06,229 --> 00:56:08,732
-Just don't make a mistake.
-Eun-yeong looks focused.

1464
00:56:09,132 --> 00:56:10,867
GLANCES…

1465
00:56:10,934 --> 00:56:12,736
Focus, Poong.

1466
00:56:12,802 --> 00:56:15,405
-I am focused.
-Please.

1467
00:56:15,472 --> 00:56:17,807
Please destroy her
just as you destroyed me four times.

1468
00:56:17,874 --> 00:56:20,677
-That's for the melon. And this.
-You're doing great.

1469
00:56:20,744 --> 00:56:21,778
Curry? Okay.

1470
00:56:21,845 --> 00:56:23,113
FRYING POWDER AND CURRY POWDER?

1471
00:56:23,179 --> 00:56:25,648
-You're mixing melon with curry?
-Curry powder.

1472
00:56:25,715 --> 00:56:26,983
-It's for the beef.
-It's the beef.

1473
00:56:27,050 --> 00:56:30,320
-<i>Ramyeon </i>soup base?
-Is that <i>ramyeon </i>soup base?

1474
00:56:30,387 --> 00:56:31,821
FLUSTERED AND COUGHING

1475
00:56:31,888 --> 00:56:34,657
Hyun-jin just noticed
the <i>ramyeon</i> soup base!

1476
00:56:34,724 --> 00:56:36,292
THE SAME AS THE EAGLES' TEAM COLOR

1477
00:56:36,359 --> 00:56:38,294
If I may speak as the top-ranking chef,

1478
00:56:38,361 --> 00:56:40,930
it would be more advantageous
for Eun-yeong to move up.

1479
00:56:40,997 --> 00:56:42,365
-I see.
-It's because

1480
00:56:42,432 --> 00:56:44,567
Poong needs to drop below second place

1481
00:56:44,634 --> 00:56:46,669
for my number of wins
to have some kind of credibility.

1482
00:56:48,705 --> 00:56:50,640
That's a good point.

1483
00:56:50,707 --> 00:56:52,742
-She's showering it.
-Great job. Nice job, Eun-yeong!

1484
00:56:52,809 --> 00:56:55,278
She showers the fish with oil.

1485
00:56:55,345 --> 00:56:57,313
Eun-yeong puts on a show.

1486
00:56:57,380 --> 00:56:59,916
-She showers the fish in oil.
-You're doing great.

1487
00:56:59,983 --> 00:57:02,051
So you can't lose the wings, right?

1488
00:57:02,118 --> 00:57:03,119
-No.
-That's right!

1489
00:57:03,186 --> 00:57:04,721
But you must continue to fry it.

1490
00:57:04,788 --> 00:57:08,391
-A whole sablefish dives into the oil.
-It looks good!

1491
00:57:09,426 --> 00:57:11,728
It turned into a monster!

1492
00:57:11,795 --> 00:57:13,029
It looks good!

1493
00:57:13,096 --> 00:57:14,130
I'm banning that phrase.

1494
00:57:14,197 --> 00:57:16,332
It looks so good, Eun-yeong.

1495
00:57:16,900 --> 00:57:18,334
THE OPPONENTS' CHEERS
MAKE TEAM POONG LOSE SPIRIT

1496
00:57:18,401 --> 00:57:19,469
MISSES

1497
00:57:19,536 --> 00:57:20,537
That…

1498
00:57:20,603 --> 00:57:22,405
Look at the way he cuts.

1499
00:57:22,472 --> 00:57:24,407
Why does he seem so clumsy today?

1500
00:57:24,474 --> 00:57:25,408
HIS CONTROL IS SHAKY

1501
00:57:25,475 --> 00:57:27,277
Why do you look so clumsy?

1502
00:57:27,343 --> 00:57:29,312
DANGEROUS

1503
00:57:29,379 --> 00:57:30,346
-Oh, no.
-Focus!

1504
00:57:30,413 --> 00:57:32,182
-How scary.
-That looks dangerous!

1505
00:57:32,248 --> 00:57:34,150
-I feel so anxious.
-Is it…

1506
00:57:34,217 --> 00:57:36,719
Is it because this will decide
who'll go to the playoffs?

1507
00:57:37,287 --> 00:57:39,355
-He looks anxious.
-He does look nervous.

1508
00:57:39,422 --> 00:57:41,191
Who cuts a melon like that?

1509
00:57:41,257 --> 00:57:43,460
Then how do you do it?
I don't know. Tell me.

1510
00:57:43,526 --> 00:57:44,727
I've never done it!

1511
00:57:44,794 --> 00:57:46,229
-Cut it like this.
-Show your support.

1512
00:57:46,296 --> 00:57:49,432
-Please be careful.
-I feel nervous.

1513
00:57:49,499 --> 00:57:50,700
I can do this.

1514
00:57:50,767 --> 00:57:52,936
How did a guy who cuts like that
win ten times?

1515
00:57:53,002 --> 00:57:54,604
Well, he won ten times,

1516
00:57:54,671 --> 00:57:55,738
but he lost fifteen times.

1517
00:57:56,306 --> 00:57:57,674
SECRET TO WINNING 10 GAMES?
SHOW UP 25 TIMES

1518
00:57:57,740 --> 00:57:59,509
-If he wins, good. If not, he'll be fine.
-I can do it.

1519
00:57:59,576 --> 00:58:02,178
-Nine minutes!
-Nine minutes!

1520
00:58:02,245 --> 00:58:03,213
We don't have much time!

1521
00:58:03,279 --> 00:58:04,848
You can do it! Stay calm.

1522
00:58:04,914 --> 00:58:07,617
-You must stay calm.
-Sung-jun, this is so hard!

1523
00:58:07,684 --> 00:58:10,220
As we mentioned before,
Chef Eun-yeong had always been

1524
00:58:10,286 --> 00:58:12,288
rather strong
against Webtoon Artist Poong.

1525
00:58:12,355 --> 00:58:14,691
-That's her.
-She fought him twice and won both times.

1526
00:58:14,757 --> 00:58:15,859
Is that soy sauce?

1527
00:58:16,993 --> 00:58:18,328
Is that soy sauce, Chef Eun-yeong?

1528
00:58:18,394 --> 00:58:20,363
-Oh, it's oyster sauce.
-It's oyster sauce.

1529
00:58:20,430 --> 00:58:21,998
She's making Chinese sauce.

1530
00:58:22,065 --> 00:58:23,867
-The sauce for the sablefish.
-It looks good.

1531
00:58:23,933 --> 00:58:24,868
"It looks good."

1532
00:58:24,934 --> 00:58:25,869
It looks good.

1533
00:58:25,935 --> 00:58:27,737
-It's odd to have your support.
-Right. Oh, is it?

1534
00:58:27,804 --> 00:58:29,706
It's odd for her to have your support.

1535
00:58:29,772 --> 00:58:31,674
-She feels awkward.
-Make a hit, Eun-yeong.

1536
00:58:32,008 --> 00:58:33,376
IT DOESN'T FAZE HIM AT ALL

1537
00:58:33,443 --> 00:58:35,078
Nine minutes left!

1538
00:58:35,144 --> 00:58:36,346
STILL NERVOUSLY CUTTING THE MELON

1539
00:58:36,412 --> 00:58:39,616
If the melon is that ripe,

1540
00:58:39,682 --> 00:58:42,051
it may turn into liquid
once it's deep-fried.

1541
00:58:42,118 --> 00:58:45,321
-Is that so?
-I'm telling you. I'm worried about that.

1542
00:58:45,388 --> 00:58:47,390
He drops the melon pieces into the batter!

1543
00:58:47,457 --> 00:58:48,925
The pieces go into the batter!

1544
00:58:48,992 --> 00:58:52,195
-The batter might peel off.
-That too.

1545
00:58:52,262 --> 00:58:54,364
-He should've coated it with powder.
-He's right.

1546
00:58:54,430 --> 00:58:55,765
-As expected…
-Will he be okay?

1547
00:58:55,832 --> 00:58:57,133
…he doesn't even know the basics.

1548
00:58:57,200 --> 00:58:59,035
A PARTICIPANT WITHOUT BASIC TRAINING

1549
00:58:59,102 --> 00:59:00,870
He's probably the first
to deep-fry a melon.

1550
00:59:00,937 --> 00:59:02,672
He's coating it with breadcrumbs.

1551
00:59:02,739 --> 00:59:05,241
-Breadcrumbs?
-Of course! I always have a plan.

1552
00:59:05,308 --> 00:59:06,910
It wasn't just that batter.

1553
00:59:06,976 --> 00:59:09,212
There's something called
the Kim Poong magic.

1554
00:59:09,279 --> 00:59:11,047
Park Eun-yeong magic.

1555
00:59:11,114 --> 00:59:13,650
FISHING OUT THE SABLEFISH FROM THE OIL

1556
00:59:13,716 --> 00:59:15,718
The sablefish looks striking.

1557
00:59:15,785 --> 00:59:18,354
Fry it one more time
and make it crunchier.

1558
00:59:18,421 --> 00:59:22,091
If Chef Eun-yeong wins, she'll make it
to the championship on her own.

1559
00:59:22,158 --> 00:59:23,026
Beef.

1560
00:59:23,092 --> 00:59:24,894
-Seven minutes.
-Seven minutes? Okay.

1561
00:59:25,361 --> 00:59:27,897
4. COAT THE CHOPPED THIN SKIRT
AND INSIDE SKIRT IN BATTER

1562
00:59:27,964 --> 00:59:29,299
That's beef.

1563
00:59:29,365 --> 00:59:31,935
He's dunking the beef into another batter.

1564
00:59:32,001 --> 00:59:34,604
What's he doing?
Why is he coating it with powder again?

1565
00:59:34,671 --> 00:59:36,406
The colors look very odd.

1566
00:59:36,472 --> 00:59:38,241
-Is it like fried chicken?
-That's right.

1567
00:59:38,308 --> 00:59:40,476
I'm deep-frying it like fried chicken,
so it'll be okay.

1568
00:59:40,543 --> 00:59:43,079
If you coat wet batter with dried powder,

1569
00:59:43,146 --> 00:59:45,248
it gets fried
like the texture of fried chicken.

1570
00:59:45,315 --> 00:59:46,316
Is that so?

1571
00:59:46,382 --> 00:59:48,651
-Seven! Down to six.
-Six minutes?

1572
00:59:49,452 --> 00:59:50,620
-He begins to deep-fry!
-What?

1573
00:59:50,687 --> 00:59:52,488
-Melon.
-The melon goes in!

1574
00:59:52,555 --> 00:59:53,923
Why aren't you using breadcrumbs?

1575
00:59:53,990 --> 00:59:55,625
Yes, right. The breadcrumbs.

1576
00:59:55,692 --> 00:59:57,226
Please! Get a grip!

1577
00:59:57,493 --> 00:59:59,128
THE HARDCORE FAN IS IN HYSTERICS

1578
00:59:59,462 --> 01:00:01,297
THE RESERVED FAN STAYS CALM

1579
01:00:01,364 --> 01:00:03,700
-I can save this.
-He had to cover it with breadcrumbs.

1580
01:00:03,766 --> 01:00:06,302
-But you can still fry it without it.
-I can.

1581
01:00:06,369 --> 01:00:08,104
I think the batter will peel off.

1582
01:00:08,171 --> 01:00:10,506
The breadcrumbs are a mess
because they got stuck to each other.

1583
01:00:10,573 --> 01:00:13,009
You have to drop it into the oil
as soon as you coat it.

1584
01:00:13,076 --> 01:00:15,845
Otherwise, it'll keep getting wet,
and more crumbs will stick to it.

1585
01:00:17,513 --> 01:00:18,648
Change it just in case.

1586
01:00:18,715 --> 01:00:20,149
SWITCHING PLANS!

1587
01:00:20,216 --> 01:00:22,151
-Yes!
-He switches!

1588
01:00:22,218 --> 01:00:24,854
-He drops it without coating it.
-It's fine.

1589
01:00:24,921 --> 01:00:27,523
-You got this in the bag!
-That means I can try different textures.

1590
01:00:27,590 --> 01:00:30,693
You're right.
You'll be able to feel two textures.

1591
01:00:30,760 --> 01:00:33,529
The same deep-fried melon
with two different textures.

1592
01:00:33,596 --> 01:00:36,933
Yes, the same melon, two textures.

1593
01:00:37,000 --> 01:00:39,535
You're doing great so far.

1594
01:00:40,103 --> 01:00:42,805
PERILLA LEAVES

1595
01:00:43,373 --> 01:00:44,941
ROASTED CHEONGYANG PEPPERS, OUT

1596
01:00:45,008 --> 01:00:46,409
Your opponent is in a rush!

1597
01:00:46,476 --> 01:00:48,277
CHEONGYANG PEPPER, GARLIC

1598
01:00:48,344 --> 01:00:50,580
-You got this in the bag.
-Really?

1599
01:00:50,647 --> 01:00:52,248
Just don't make any mistakes.

1600
01:00:52,315 --> 01:00:53,282
WE'LL WIN IF YOU DON'T!

1601
01:00:53,349 --> 01:00:55,785
Chef Eun-yeong grinds pepper.

1602
01:00:55,852 --> 01:00:58,521
She's trying to make a sauce
by grinding burnt pepper.

1603
01:00:58,588 --> 01:00:59,689
Is it just pepper?

1604
01:00:59,756 --> 01:01:01,090
Peppers and perilla leaves.

1605
01:01:01,157 --> 01:01:03,292
-Perilla leaves.
-And garlic.

1606
01:01:03,359 --> 01:01:05,328
Peppers, perilla leaves, and garlic.

1607
01:01:05,395 --> 01:01:07,830
-Will they finish in time?
-Is that the sauce?

1608
01:01:07,897 --> 01:01:09,532
They somehow always do.

1609
01:01:09,599 --> 01:01:11,067
Five minutes left.

1610
01:01:11,134 --> 01:01:13,102
-Five minutes left.
-Five minutes, Jung-hwan!

1611
01:01:13,169 --> 01:01:14,404
Please report from the kitchen.

1612
01:01:14,470 --> 01:01:16,406
You got this,
as long as the fish turns out nicely.

1613
01:01:16,472 --> 01:01:17,540
THE PACEMAKER

1614
01:01:17,607 --> 01:01:19,142
The sablefish!

1615
01:01:19,208 --> 01:01:21,911
-It does look kind of scary.
-It looks like a monster.

1616
01:01:21,978 --> 01:01:23,079
Yes, it does.

1617
01:01:23,146 --> 01:01:24,247
The melon sauce.

1618
01:01:24,313 --> 01:01:25,648
STARTS MAKING THE SAUCE

1619
01:01:25,715 --> 01:01:27,583
He's using the soft part near the seeds.

1620
01:01:27,650 --> 01:01:29,318
Melon and sugar?

1621
01:01:31,220 --> 01:01:34,123
Do you have a sweet tooth, Hyun-jin?

1622
01:01:34,190 --> 01:01:36,726
-I'm not a huge fan.
-I see.

1623
01:01:36,793 --> 01:01:38,127
Nothing too sweet?

1624
01:01:38,194 --> 01:01:39,362
But do you like melons?

1625
01:01:39,429 --> 01:01:42,665
-Yes, I do like the fruit.
-You do? That's a relief.

1626
01:01:42,732 --> 01:01:44,834
Jung-hwan, do you think
the fritters are coming along?

1627
01:01:44,901 --> 01:01:48,404
The beef still has to be fried
and the sauce still has to be made.

1628
01:01:48,471 --> 01:01:50,339
Chef Eun-yeong finished
deep-frying the sablefish.

1629
01:01:50,406 --> 01:01:51,841
She just needs to make the sauce.

1630
01:01:51,908 --> 01:01:53,276
-Don't make it too salty.
-Not too salty.

1631
01:01:53,342 --> 01:01:54,644
SUGAR, SALT

1632
01:01:54,911 --> 01:01:55,745
GROUND PEPPER

1633
01:01:55,812 --> 01:01:58,681
-You'll lose if it's salty.
-He's doing his best cheering her on.

1634
01:01:58,748 --> 01:02:00,416
Vinegar.

1635
01:02:00,483 --> 01:02:02,251
-She'll lose if it's too salty?
-She will.

1636
01:02:02,318 --> 01:02:03,619
Why are your hands shaking?

1637
01:02:03,686 --> 01:02:04,687
-I'm cheering.
-You are?

1638
01:02:04,754 --> 01:02:06,155
You can do it, Eun-yeong!

1639
01:02:06,556 --> 01:02:07,957
HE STOPPED CHEERING LONG AGO

1640
01:02:08,024 --> 01:02:09,592
-I can do it. Don't worry.
-Three minutes.

1641
01:02:09,659 --> 01:02:11,127
Don't worry. I'll let you move up.

1642
01:02:11,194 --> 01:02:12,428
-Please, brother!
-Nam-no!

1643
01:02:12,495 --> 01:02:15,131
THE CHEER CAPTAINS ARE MORE DESPERATE

1644
01:02:15,198 --> 01:02:18,601
-Poong begins to deep-fry the beef.
-I can do this.

1645
01:02:18,668 --> 01:02:21,270
The beef is coming along fine.

1646
01:02:21,337 --> 01:02:23,806
We're good now. That beef looks delicious.

1647
01:02:24,273 --> 01:02:25,708
EUN-YEONG FINISHES THE SAUCE!

1648
01:02:26,275 --> 01:02:27,977
POURING BOILING OIL OVER PEPPER SAUCE!

1649
01:02:28,044 --> 01:02:30,513
-Look at that.
-She's pouring boiling oil over peppers.

1650
01:02:31,147 --> 01:02:33,316
INCREASING EXPECTATION

1651
01:02:33,382 --> 01:02:34,517
How amazing. It looks so good.

1652
01:02:34,584 --> 01:02:35,885
-It smells good.
-Is that for the fish?

1653
01:02:35,952 --> 01:02:37,386
-I knew you'd do it, Eun-yeong.
-That's right.

1654
01:02:37,453 --> 01:02:39,522
What about the sauce his mother made?

1655
01:02:39,589 --> 01:02:43,126
-I gave it up to present a new flavor.
-For something new.

1656
01:02:43,192 --> 01:02:46,529
-I'll try the pepper sauce for the fish.
-The pepper sauce!

1657
01:02:46,596 --> 01:02:48,664
I will try this sauce.

1658
01:02:48,731 --> 01:02:51,634
-The sauce that'll go on top of the fish!
-The pepper sauce!

1659
01:02:51,701 --> 01:02:53,069
The sablefish sauce!

1660
01:02:53,136 --> 01:02:55,938
So? Can it strike Poong out?

1661
01:02:56,005 --> 01:02:58,040
Can it strike Poong out?

1662
01:02:58,841 --> 01:03:00,710
-It must be spicy.
-My gosh.

1663
01:03:00,777 --> 01:03:02,411
He just might get struck out.

1664
01:03:02,478 --> 01:03:04,447
LET'S PLAY THE OUT JINGLE

1665
01:03:05,081 --> 01:03:06,582
POONG GOES BYE-BYE

1666
01:03:06,649 --> 01:03:08,017
<i>It's so good.</i>

1667
01:03:08,985 --> 01:03:09,986
That's the Goddess of Chinese Cuisine!

1668
01:03:10,286 --> 01:03:11,521
HYUN-JIN IS PLEASED

1669
01:03:11,587 --> 01:03:13,723
The roasted flavor of the pepper
tastes absolutely amazing.

1670
01:03:13,790 --> 01:03:16,025
You're doing great.
Shouldn't you fry it once again?

1671
01:03:16,092 --> 01:03:17,059
I should.

1672
01:03:17,126 --> 01:03:19,195
One more time. A minute and a half left.

1673
01:03:19,262 --> 01:03:21,364
Great work! The last deep-fry.

1674
01:03:22,632 --> 01:03:24,000
The third fry.

1675
01:03:25,134 --> 01:03:28,204
The melon isn't getting fried
as quickly as I thought it would.

1676
01:03:28,271 --> 01:03:29,172
-No?
-No.

1677
01:03:29,238 --> 01:03:31,240
The sauce! Is it burning?

1678
01:03:31,307 --> 01:03:33,242
The sauce!

1679
01:03:33,309 --> 01:03:34,177
Stop confusing me.

1680
01:03:34,243 --> 01:03:36,679
Will you please check the sauce?

1681
01:03:37,246 --> 01:03:39,549
Those are done,
but I can see the melon inside.

1682
01:03:39,615 --> 01:03:41,851
The melon inside is peeking out.

1683
01:03:41,918 --> 01:03:44,086
It's half-fritter, half-melon.

1684
01:03:44,654 --> 01:03:46,856
IT'S NEITHER THIS NOR THAT

1685
01:03:47,190 --> 01:03:48,524
SETTING THE MELON ASIDE

1686
01:03:48,791 --> 01:03:50,393
THE BEEF FRITTERS ARE OUT FIRST

1687
01:03:50,960 --> 01:03:52,528
SLIPS

1688
01:03:52,595 --> 01:03:55,131
-Damn it.
-He said it. "Damn it."

1689
01:03:55,198 --> 01:03:56,933
-A minute and a half. Stay calm.
-The melon sauce.

1690
01:03:57,433 --> 01:03:58,935
CAN HE TURN THE TABLES?

1691
01:03:59,001 --> 01:04:00,736
Should I try the melon sauce?

1692
01:04:00,803 --> 01:04:03,806
-The melon sauce! Nam-no looks depressed.
-The melon sauce!

1693
01:04:03,873 --> 01:04:07,076
-Things aren't going smoothly for Poong.
-He looks anxious!

1694
01:04:07,143 --> 01:04:09,078
-Let me try the melon sauce.
-The melon sauce.

1695
01:04:09,145 --> 01:04:10,913
-I think it'll be too sweet.
-A minute left.

1696
01:04:10,980 --> 01:04:12,348
-He poured sugar in.
-The taste of the melon sauce!

1697
01:04:12,949 --> 01:04:14,183
So, Jung-hwan?

1698
01:04:14,750 --> 01:04:16,152
Do you feel happy?

1699
01:04:16,219 --> 01:04:17,053
He looks serious.

1700
01:04:17,119 --> 01:04:19,055
RAPIDLY LOSING HOPE

1701
01:04:19,121 --> 01:04:20,590
Are you happy?

1702
01:04:20,656 --> 01:04:22,758
It's still too early to be happy!

1703
01:04:22,825 --> 01:04:24,894
So far, he's unhappy.

1704
01:04:25,461 --> 01:04:26,295
AN EMERGENCY MEASURE!

1705
01:04:26,362 --> 01:04:27,330
Fifty seconds left!

1706
01:04:27,396 --> 01:04:30,266
-Butter? Okay! Melon and butter.
-Melon and butter.

1707
01:04:30,333 --> 01:04:31,934
Melon and butter?

1708
01:04:32,001 --> 01:04:33,769
Will it go well with the fritters?

1709
01:04:33,836 --> 01:04:35,304
Take the fish out.

1710
01:04:35,371 --> 01:04:37,607
You have to serve your dish first.

1711
01:04:37,673 --> 01:04:39,709
-Please wrap it up!
-Wrap it up!

1712
01:04:39,775 --> 01:04:41,043
4. ADD STARCH WATER AND SESAME OIL

1713
01:04:41,110 --> 01:04:42,578
SERVES THE SOY-BASED SAUCE FIRST

1714
01:04:42,645 --> 01:04:44,580
Excellent job!

1715
01:04:45,314 --> 01:04:46,649
AND DROPS THE SABLEFISH ON TOP!

1716
01:04:46,716 --> 01:04:47,683
It looks amazing.

1717
01:04:48,251 --> 01:04:49,685
AS FOR KIM POONG…

1718
01:04:49,752 --> 01:04:50,987
He's serving it in that?

1719
01:04:51,053 --> 01:04:53,322
-What is that?
-He's using the melon as a bowl.

1720
01:04:53,389 --> 01:04:55,424
The fritters will get soggy.

1721
01:04:55,491 --> 01:04:59,528
I think he's trying to serve
melon fritters in the melon bowl.

1722
01:04:59,929 --> 01:05:01,163
THE BALLPARK IS MURMURING

1723
01:05:01,564 --> 01:05:03,165
I'LL SHOW YOU A 9TH-INNING MIRACLE

1724
01:05:03,232 --> 01:05:05,434
Chef Eun-yeong is almost done.

1725
01:05:05,501 --> 01:05:07,403
-The sauce was delicious.
-My gosh.

1726
01:05:07,470 --> 01:05:08,871
-Go, Eun-yeong!
-It looks so good.

1727
01:05:08,938 --> 01:05:10,239
-Ten seconds.
-Ten seconds!

1728
01:05:10,306 --> 01:05:11,307
No, stop eating that!

1729
01:05:11,374 --> 01:05:12,341
OKAY, OKAY…

1730
01:05:12,408 --> 01:05:14,210
-Seven. Six.
-Eun-yeong is done!

1731
01:05:14,277 --> 01:05:15,478
Eun-yeong finishes.

1732
01:05:15,544 --> 01:05:17,179
-Eun-yeong is done.
-Four. Three.

1733
01:05:17,246 --> 01:05:19,148
-Two. One.
-The sauce.

1734
01:05:19,215 --> 01:05:20,716
That was for the sauce.

1735
01:05:20,783 --> 01:05:22,318
FINISHING WITH THE MELON SAUCE!

1736
01:05:24,153 --> 01:05:27,156
A PLAY TOTALLY OUT OF LEFT FIELD

1737
01:05:27,223 --> 01:05:29,225
-He's done.
-They're both done.

1738
01:05:29,292 --> 01:05:31,661
-Poong finishes too.
-I think you won.

1739
01:05:31,727 --> 01:05:33,996
-No.
-Team Eun-yeong is sure of victory.

1740
01:05:34,063 --> 01:05:35,164
All done.

1741
01:05:35,231 --> 01:05:36,899
-You never know.
-They look good.

1742
01:05:36,966 --> 01:05:37,967
IT'S NOT OVER TILL IT'S OVER

1743
01:05:38,034 --> 01:05:40,269
That one looks really good.

1744
01:05:40,336 --> 01:05:42,438
The presentation is worlds apart.

1745
01:05:42,505 --> 01:05:44,273
I don't think you even have to try it.

1746
01:05:44,340 --> 01:05:47,610
-He won't even have to try it.
-You never know.

1747
01:05:47,677 --> 01:05:51,314
And now, two deep-fried dishes
are served for Hyun-jin to enjoy.

1748
01:05:51,380 --> 01:05:52,515
I have a feeling

1749
01:05:52,581 --> 01:05:55,117
that he already made his decision.

1750
01:05:55,418 --> 01:05:56,919
ALREADY?

1751
01:05:56,986 --> 01:05:58,888
As you can see, visually speaking,

1752
01:05:58,955 --> 01:06:00,523
-it's game over.
-It's over.

1753
01:06:00,589 --> 01:06:01,657
But I'm excited to try it

1754
01:06:01,724 --> 01:06:04,694
because he still manages to win
after cooking up something weird.

1755
01:06:04,760 --> 01:06:07,263
-I'm looking forward to it.
-That's his magic.

1756
01:06:07,330 --> 01:06:09,899
-First, Chef Eun-yeong's dish.
-Let's go!

1757
01:06:09,966 --> 01:06:11,033
<i>Kim Poong, Strikeout.</i>

1758
01:06:11,100 --> 01:06:14,170
FROM HEAD TO TAIL

1759
01:06:14,670 --> 01:06:17,673
A WHOLE FRIED SABLEFISH,
WITH KOREAN AND CHINESE SAUCE

1760
01:06:18,174 --> 01:06:21,744
CHEF PARK EUN-YEONG'S
KIM POONG, STRIKEOUT!

1761
01:06:21,811 --> 01:06:23,679
Look at that visual.

1762
01:06:23,746 --> 01:06:26,649
-It's a monster. She made a monster.
-It looks good.

1763
01:06:26,716 --> 01:06:28,551
Break off the meat,

1764
01:06:28,617 --> 01:06:31,988
dip it in the sauce on the dish,
and then top it with the pepper sauce.

1765
01:06:32,054 --> 01:06:34,256
First, dip it in the sauce.

1766
01:06:34,323 --> 01:06:35,558
GASP

1767
01:06:35,624 --> 01:06:36,692
THICK MEAT

1768
01:06:36,759 --> 01:06:39,795
Hyun-jin looks shocked too.

1769
01:06:39,862 --> 01:06:41,831
He's excited for the first time.

1770
01:06:41,897 --> 01:06:44,266
-Top it with pepper sauce.
-It looks scary.

1771
01:06:44,333 --> 01:06:45,601
It looks good.

1772
01:06:45,668 --> 01:06:46,936
Goodness, the sauce.

1773
01:06:47,336 --> 01:06:48,871
COOLING IT DOWN

1774
01:06:48,938 --> 01:06:50,006
It must be hot.

1775
01:06:51,741 --> 01:06:53,309
DRIPPING

1776
01:06:53,376 --> 01:06:55,411
He takes a big mouthful.

1777
01:06:55,478 --> 01:06:58,080
-Fried food is how he stays in shape.
-It was fried food.

1778
01:06:58,147 --> 01:06:59,615
-It looks good.
-He nodded.

1779
01:06:59,682 --> 01:07:01,117
This is

1780
01:07:01,183 --> 01:07:02,485
-really good.
-Is it?

1781
01:07:02,551 --> 01:07:04,286
-It's over.
-You did it!

1782
01:07:04,353 --> 01:07:06,489
-It's so good.
-You got this.

1783
01:07:06,555 --> 01:07:08,791
There's a bit of spiciness
from the pepper,

1784
01:07:08,858 --> 01:07:11,827
as well as sweetness from this sauce.

1785
01:07:11,894 --> 01:07:13,696
The balance is wonderful.

1786
01:07:13,763 --> 01:07:15,865
I've only had deep-fried pollack pieces,

1787
01:07:15,931 --> 01:07:19,001
so this is my first time
eating a whole fried fish.

1788
01:07:19,068 --> 01:07:22,938
I think I can probably finish
one type of deep-fried food for once.

1789
01:07:23,205 --> 01:07:24,907
I'M SO CURIOUS

1790
01:07:24,974 --> 01:07:25,808
I expected as much.

1791
01:07:25,875 --> 01:07:26,709
THE TWO ARE DIVIDED

1792
01:07:27,410 --> 01:07:29,045
He takes yet another bite.

1793
01:07:29,111 --> 01:07:30,713
It looks so good.

1794
01:07:30,780 --> 01:07:32,381
-So good.
-You need to stop.

1795
01:07:32,448 --> 01:07:33,916
It must be so good.

1796
01:07:35,317 --> 01:07:36,452
It really must be good.

1797
01:07:36,519 --> 01:07:37,353
THUMBS UP

1798
01:07:38,020 --> 01:07:38,854
A thumbs-up.

1799
01:07:39,155 --> 01:07:40,322
JOY, SORROW

1800
01:07:40,389 --> 01:07:42,024
She receives praise.

1801
01:07:42,091 --> 01:07:44,794
-It's really good.
-The Goddess of Chinese Cuisine indeed.

1802
01:07:44,860 --> 01:07:46,462
I'm so curious.

1803
01:07:46,529 --> 01:07:48,330
-Can Poong beat that?
-That was Eun-yeong's dish.

1804
01:07:48,397 --> 01:07:51,233
Next up, Webtoon Artist Poong.
Is there a twist to his fate?

1805
01:07:51,801 --> 01:07:54,904
DEEP-FRIED BEEF & MELON

1806
01:07:55,438 --> 01:07:57,873
AND MELON SAUCE SERVED IN A MELON BOWL

1807
01:07:58,474 --> 01:08:01,444
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S
I AM DEEP-FRYING MELON

1808
01:08:01,510 --> 01:08:03,579
Does he begin with beef or melon?

1809
01:08:03,646 --> 01:08:05,047
Try the beef first.

1810
01:08:05,114 --> 01:08:06,982
Then dip the melon fritter in the sauce.

1811
01:08:07,049 --> 01:08:10,386
-Do I eat the beef as is?
-Yes, eat it as is. Enjoy.

1812
01:08:10,453 --> 01:08:12,488
-But dip the melon in the sauce.
-The beef fritter.

1813
01:08:15,524 --> 01:08:17,560
His batter was sort of unique.

1814
01:08:17,626 --> 01:08:20,729
<i>-He used curry powder and </i>ramyeon<i> base.</i>
<i>-And </i>ramyeon<i> soup base.</i>

1815
01:08:20,796 --> 01:08:23,299
I can really smell the curry.

1816
01:08:23,365 --> 01:08:26,268
-But not much of the <i>ramyeon </i>soup base.
-Right.

1817
01:08:26,335 --> 01:08:28,571
Just think of it
like ordinary fried chicken.

1818
01:08:28,637 --> 01:08:30,739
-I made fried chicken with beef.
-Fried chicken-beef.

1819
01:08:30,806 --> 01:08:32,942
-I'm dying to try this.
-He's trying the melon.

1820
01:08:33,008 --> 01:08:35,010
He's going for the melon.

1821
01:08:35,077 --> 01:08:37,880
You might burn your mouth, so be careful.

1822
01:08:37,947 --> 01:08:38,848
Should I get lots of sauce?

1823
01:08:38,914 --> 01:08:40,649
-A lot?
-As much as you like.

1824
01:08:40,716 --> 01:08:43,118
-Yes, this is it.
-It's all the way in.

1825
01:08:43,185 --> 01:08:46,455
The game was already over
when it came to the presentation.

1826
01:08:46,522 --> 01:08:47,790
-Wait.
-No!

1827
01:08:47,857 --> 01:08:49,258
It fell out.

1828
01:08:49,325 --> 01:08:52,094
It would be better if you picked a melon
covered in some breadcrumbs.

1829
01:08:52,161 --> 01:08:54,463
-Try this one.
-That way, you can get more sauce.

1830
01:08:54,530 --> 01:08:56,065
Does he have to pick and choose?

1831
01:08:56,132 --> 01:08:57,967
-You can just eat it.
-This is it.

1832
01:08:58,033 --> 01:08:59,135
What will it be like?

1833
01:08:59,201 --> 01:09:00,736
I wonder what that's like.

1834
01:09:00,803 --> 01:09:02,104
STUFFING IT INTO HIS TINY(?) MOUTH

1835
01:09:02,171 --> 01:09:03,639
It's a melon fritter.

1836
01:09:03,706 --> 01:09:05,474
He said he enjoys it as a fruit.

1837
01:09:05,541 --> 01:09:06,775
PFFT!

1838
01:09:07,343 --> 01:09:09,612
AT LEAST HE MANAGED TO MAKE HIM LAUGH

1839
01:09:09,678 --> 01:09:10,746
-Is it good?
-No.

1840
01:09:11,180 --> 01:09:13,315
NERVOUS, IT'S A GOOD SIGN!

1841
01:09:13,782 --> 01:09:17,786
IS THIS LAUGHTER POSITIVE? NEGATIVE?

1842
01:09:18,954 --> 01:09:19,922
It's a melon fritter.

1843
01:09:19,989 --> 01:09:21,757
It's like a cream puff.

1844
01:09:22,091 --> 01:09:23,859
SURPRISED

1845
01:09:23,926 --> 01:09:27,496
<i>-Does the melon inside melt away?</i>
<i>-Yes.</i>

1846
01:09:27,563 --> 01:09:29,832
-Was this intentional?
-Yes.

1847
01:09:29,899 --> 01:09:32,401
-I wanted to make it like cream puffs.
-Like cream puffs.

1848
01:09:32,468 --> 01:09:34,003
-That's right.
-Wait, so…

1849
01:09:34,069 --> 01:09:36,172
THIS MAKES NO SENSE

1850
01:09:37,740 --> 01:09:41,777
It was the kind of dish
I expected Webtoon Artist Poong to make.

1851
01:09:42,811 --> 01:09:45,915
It looks like he had a taste of
what he imagined his food would be like.

1852
01:09:45,981 --> 01:09:47,082
This won't be easy.

1853
01:09:47,149 --> 01:09:48,484
WHY IS THIS SO GOOD?

1854
01:09:48,551 --> 01:09:51,287
-Did the magic work?
-There may be a twist.

1855
01:09:51,353 --> 01:09:52,855
HE'S ENCHANTED!

1856
01:09:52,922 --> 01:09:55,157
It must be good.
It tastes even better after eating fish.

1857
01:09:55,224 --> 01:09:58,894
-He's eating that as dessert right now.
-Isn't it?

1858
01:09:58,961 --> 01:10:00,162
It's a dessert.

1859
01:10:00,229 --> 01:10:01,330
A FLAWLESS DESSERT

1860
01:10:01,397 --> 01:10:04,667
Let's try Chef Eun-yeong's dish first.

1861
01:10:04,733 --> 01:10:06,402
Let's all try it.

1862
01:10:06,468 --> 01:10:07,937
OH, WOW

1863
01:10:08,571 --> 01:10:09,905
This is nice.

1864
01:10:11,607 --> 01:10:13,275
-This is good.
-I like the roasted pepper smell.

1865
01:10:13,342 --> 01:10:15,911
DOPPELGANGER FISH

1866
01:10:18,013 --> 01:10:18,948
It's so good.

1867
01:10:19,582 --> 01:10:21,350
It was just as Hyun-jin said.

1868
01:10:21,417 --> 01:10:24,653
The sweetness to spiciness ratio

1869
01:10:25,221 --> 01:10:26,822
is just perfect.

1870
01:10:26,889 --> 01:10:28,057
It's really pleasing.

1871
01:10:28,123 --> 01:10:30,059
It's perfectly balanced.

1872
01:10:30,125 --> 01:10:32,361
-Delightfully spicy.
-Delightfully spicy.

1873
01:10:32,428 --> 01:10:35,531
I would call this
the textbook of deep-fried dishes.

1874
01:10:35,598 --> 01:10:37,666
It's crunchy, yet the inside is soft.

1875
01:10:37,733 --> 01:10:39,568
It's the best dish she has made yet.

1876
01:10:40,803 --> 01:10:42,037
I knew you'd do it.

1877
01:10:42,104 --> 01:10:44,940
Objectively speaking,
I think it's only right

1878
01:10:45,007 --> 01:10:46,375
for Chef Eun-yeong to go up.

1879
01:10:46,942 --> 01:10:48,444
WHAT IS HE SAYING?

1880
01:10:48,510 --> 01:10:49,411
-Do you think so?
-It's so good.

1881
01:10:49,478 --> 01:10:51,347
Let's hear from Nam-no.

1882
01:10:51,413 --> 01:10:53,082
I don't like it.

1883
01:10:53,148 --> 01:10:55,551
You finished everything. I only see bones.

1884
01:10:55,618 --> 01:10:58,187
-Only the bones remain.
-We can see your dish right there.

1885
01:10:58,654 --> 01:11:00,356
NOT A MAN OF HIS WORD

1886
01:11:00,422 --> 01:11:02,524
She used boiling oil
on the fish and the sauce, right?

1887
01:11:02,591 --> 01:11:05,694
<i>Did that bring out</i>
<i>the overall aroma like this?</i>

1888
01:11:05,761 --> 01:11:07,663
And the umami flavor is strong too.

1889
01:11:07,730 --> 01:11:10,599
-I knew it.
-It was quite a luxurious dish.

1890
01:11:10,666 --> 01:11:12,868
Did you copy Chef Chinglai's recipe?

1891
01:11:12,935 --> 01:11:15,638
-This is my personal creation.
-A personal creation.

1892
01:11:15,704 --> 01:11:17,640
-How long will it go on?
-Personal creation.

1893
01:11:17,706 --> 01:11:20,943
-Next, Webtoon Artist Poong's dish.
-The melon fritter.

1894
01:11:21,010 --> 01:11:23,279
I've been dying to find out.

1895
01:11:24,546 --> 01:11:26,782
WIDE-EYED

1896
01:11:28,083 --> 01:11:30,119
INCREDULOUS LAUGH

1897
01:11:30,619 --> 01:11:32,888
HE CAN'T STOP LAUGHING

1898
01:11:32,955 --> 01:11:34,723
-Huh?
-What is this?

1899
01:11:34,790 --> 01:11:36,492
The sauce is really good.

1900
01:11:36,558 --> 01:11:38,160
My gosh. This is insane.

1901
01:11:38,227 --> 01:11:39,495
HOW DOES THIS MAKE ANY SENSE?

1902
01:11:39,862 --> 01:11:41,497
THEY CAN'T DENY HOW DELICIOUS IT IS

1903
01:11:41,563 --> 01:11:44,333
-Isn't this so good?
-The sauce is amazing.

1904
01:11:44,400 --> 01:11:45,601
Dip it in the sauce.

1905
01:11:45,668 --> 01:11:48,003
HOW ABOUT THE DOUBTFUL SHIN-SOO?

1906
01:11:50,973 --> 01:11:52,775
KIM POONG'S MAGIC AT WORK

1907
01:11:52,841 --> 01:11:54,376
-Why is this good?
-Poong, what the heck?

1908
01:11:54,443 --> 01:11:55,678
He took a blow from Poong.

1909
01:11:55,744 --> 01:11:57,313
This is the biggest twist.

1910
01:11:57,379 --> 01:11:59,248
I just got chills.

1911
01:11:59,682 --> 01:12:00,783
BUMPY

1912
01:12:00,849 --> 01:12:02,985
He really got goose bumps!

1913
01:12:03,385 --> 01:12:06,055
THE MONSTER CHEF & MY FRIDGE GAVE BIRTH TO
LIVES UP TO HIS NAME

1914
01:12:06,121 --> 01:12:08,090
-It's the butter.
-I realized what it means

1915
01:12:08,157 --> 01:12:10,693
-to have something melt in your mouth.
-And it's buttery.

1916
01:12:10,759 --> 01:12:12,094
It just disappeared.

1917
01:12:12,161 --> 01:12:13,962
I thought I could probably chew the melon,

1918
01:12:14,029 --> 01:12:16,465
but it worked as sauce on the inside.

1919
01:12:16,532 --> 01:12:19,268
-It was like custard cream.
-It turned into cream.

1920
01:12:19,335 --> 01:12:23,305
And why does this sauce have
layers of flavors? I taste dairy too.

1921
01:12:23,372 --> 01:12:26,241
<i>-It's butter.</i>
<i>-He said he added a spoonful of butter.</i>

1922
01:12:26,308 --> 01:12:28,077
<i>I didn't know it could turn out like this.</i>

1923
01:12:28,143 --> 01:12:29,111
THE POWER OF ONE SPOON OF BUTTER

1924
01:12:29,178 --> 01:12:31,580
-Kim Poong's magic is real.
-It is.

1925
01:12:31,647 --> 01:12:33,649
That left everyone in shock.

1926
01:12:33,716 --> 01:12:34,917
KIM POONG IS RIGHT AT HER HEELS

1927
01:12:34,983 --> 01:12:38,420
-It's an emergency.
-I didn't expect it to taste like this.

1928
01:12:38,487 --> 01:12:39,621
It felt like

1929
01:12:39,688 --> 01:12:44,059
a custard bun
had popped right in my mouth.

1930
01:12:44,126 --> 01:12:46,995
The beef fritters he served first

1931
01:12:47,062 --> 01:12:49,832
also tasted like chicken-fried steak,
which has "chicken" in the name,

1932
01:12:49,898 --> 01:12:52,334
-but is actually made with beef.
-You're right.

1933
01:12:52,401 --> 01:12:54,103
You two lived in America,

1934
01:12:54,169 --> 01:12:56,705
so I'm sure
he even considered that aspect.

1935
01:12:56,772 --> 01:12:59,641
-Was it that profound?
-It doesn't seem like it.

1936
01:12:59,708 --> 01:13:03,245
-Chef Jong-won is over-interpreting.
-What does he hold against you?

1937
01:13:03,312 --> 01:13:05,247
Has he been inside my mind?

1938
01:13:05,314 --> 01:13:07,282
I want to hear
Sung-jun's objective opinion.

1939
01:13:07,349 --> 01:13:09,351
Who eats stuff this sweet these days?

1940
01:13:10,185 --> 01:13:12,388
YOU, JUST 5 MINUTES AGO

1941
01:13:12,454 --> 01:13:14,723
I vote for the Goddess of Chinese Cuisine,
Eun-yeong.

1942
01:13:14,790 --> 01:13:16,825
-She's my only choice.
-All right.

1943
01:13:16,892 --> 01:13:18,327
You must decide now.

1944
01:13:18,394 --> 01:13:20,162
-You must decide.
-It must be hard.

1945
01:13:20,229 --> 01:13:23,165
It feels like an extra inning,
like the 11th inning.

1946
01:13:23,232 --> 01:13:25,267
-It must be hard.
-It's a close fight.

1947
01:13:25,334 --> 01:13:28,137
Kim Poong versus Park Eun-yeong.

1948
01:13:28,203 --> 01:13:30,706
-The result is very important.
-I have no idea who'll win.

1949
01:13:30,773 --> 01:13:33,075
<i>Press one for Park Eun-yeong,</i>

1950
01:13:33,142 --> 01:13:34,910
<i>and press two for Kim Poong.</i>

1951
01:13:34,977 --> 01:13:37,846
Now, Hyun-jin's choice will

1952
01:13:37,913 --> 01:13:39,715
-change the show forever!
-Please, Eun-yeong.

1953
01:13:39,782 --> 01:13:42,117
-This decision can change everything.
-That's right.

1954
01:13:42,184 --> 01:13:44,253
-Did you press it?
-I did.

1955
01:13:44,319 --> 01:13:46,422
Depending on what his choice was,

1956
01:13:46,488 --> 01:13:48,724
one person will be eliminated,

1957
01:13:48,791 --> 01:13:50,492
while the other one moves up.

1958
01:13:50,559 --> 01:13:52,361
-Who did Hyun-jin choose?
-Please.

1959
01:13:52,428 --> 01:13:54,129
Let's find out!

1960
01:13:54,196 --> 01:13:55,130
Show us!

1961
01:13:55,197 --> 01:13:56,665
Korean Deep-Fry Monster.

1962
01:13:56,732 --> 01:13:58,367
This is more nerve-racking than my round.

1963
01:13:58,434 --> 01:14:00,135
If Eun-yeong wins this round,

1964
01:14:00,202 --> 01:14:02,738
-she can play in the postseason.
-Please.

1965
01:14:02,805 --> 01:14:04,406
But if Poong wins,

1966
01:14:04,473 --> 01:14:06,708
he will remain as the sole 2nd place

1967
01:14:06,775 --> 01:14:11,280
-and take Nam-no into the championship.
-Please!

1968
01:14:11,346 --> 01:14:15,150
Which dish did Hyun-jin choose?

1969
01:14:15,217 --> 01:14:17,619
-Who deep-fried it better?
-Let's go, Eun-yeong.

1970
01:14:17,686 --> 01:14:19,288
-Please!
-A lot is at stake.

1971
01:14:19,354 --> 01:14:20,656
What's the result?

1972
01:14:22,591 --> 01:14:23,692
What's the result?

1973
01:14:24,326 --> 01:14:25,527
PARK EUN-YEONG WINS

1974
01:14:25,594 --> 01:14:27,696
CHEF PARK EUN-YEONG'S
KIM POONG, STRIKEOUT WINS

1975
01:14:27,763 --> 01:14:29,465
Park Eun-yeong wins!

1976
01:14:30,032 --> 01:14:31,233
STRIKEOUT

1977
01:14:31,733 --> 01:14:33,368
Eun-yeong strikes him out!

1978
01:14:33,435 --> 01:14:34,536
Kim Poong, Strikeout!

1979
01:14:35,103 --> 01:14:38,373
I thought it was already decided
as soon as the dishes were served.

1980
01:14:38,440 --> 01:14:40,375
<i>The visuals played a huge role.</i>

1981
01:14:40,442 --> 01:14:41,343
But…

1982
01:14:42,778 --> 01:14:43,946
KIM POONG MAGIC LEFT HIM SPEECHLESS

1983
01:14:44,012 --> 01:14:45,347
He caught up by a lot.

1984
01:14:45,414 --> 01:14:47,382
-He caught up.
-But really, yes.

1985
01:14:47,449 --> 01:14:50,919
As I mentioned before,
it felt like extra innings.

1986
01:14:50,986 --> 01:14:53,255
But from the start,

1987
01:14:53,322 --> 01:14:57,993
I loved the balance between the sweetness
and the spiciness of this dish.

1988
01:14:58,060 --> 01:15:00,996
It's still quite impressive
that he caught up this much.

1989
01:15:01,063 --> 01:15:04,633
Thanks to Hyun-jin's decision,

1990
01:15:04,700 --> 01:15:10,272
all five chefs for the championship,
the postseason rounds, have been decided.

1991
01:15:10,339 --> 01:15:11,940
The five have been decided.

1992
01:15:12,007 --> 01:15:14,109
Nam-no does not make the cut…

1993
01:15:14,176 --> 01:15:16,245
-We didn't have a chance.
-…as well as Sung-jun.

1994
01:15:16,311 --> 01:15:19,314
-Eun-yeong makes the postseason.
-Excellent.

1995
01:15:19,381 --> 01:15:21,183
Why don't we hear from her?

1996
01:15:21,250 --> 01:15:24,019
I had a huge headache
from the moment I said the dish's name,

1997
01:15:24,086 --> 01:15:27,155
but I gave it my best
despite that huge headache.

1998
01:15:27,222 --> 01:15:29,858
I'm very glad
that Hyun-jin seemed to have noticed.

1999
01:15:29,925 --> 01:15:32,261
-Shouldn't you thank me too?
-So what's it called again?

2000
01:15:32,828 --> 01:15:35,163
Kim Poong, Strikeout!

2001
01:15:35,831 --> 01:15:37,165
KIM POONG, STRIKEOUT

2002
01:15:38,166 --> 01:15:40,269
-Congratulations.
-She's the mascot of the show.

2003
01:15:40,335 --> 01:15:42,437
Please put a star on Chef Eun-yeong.

2004
01:15:42,504 --> 01:15:44,606
She makes the postseason

2005
01:15:44,673 --> 01:15:46,675
with nine wins and six losses!

2006
01:15:46,742 --> 01:15:49,478
-She made the postseason.
-She'll join the playoffs!

2007
01:15:49,545 --> 01:15:50,612
Congratulations.

2008
01:15:51,313 --> 01:15:54,283
He's a legendary player
who set many first records.

2009
01:15:54,349 --> 01:15:56,451
-We can look forward to it, right?
-It'll be amazing.

2010
01:15:56,518 --> 01:15:57,686
He has lots of healthy food.

2011
01:15:57,753 --> 01:15:59,621
I always steal his food,

2012
01:15:59,688 --> 01:16:01,323
saying, "Can I take this?"

2013
01:16:01,390 --> 01:16:03,025
We present his fridge!

2014
01:16:03,091 --> 01:16:04,426
It's fully loaded.

2015
01:16:04,493 --> 01:16:05,894
I'm mostly into meat,

2016
01:16:05,961 --> 01:16:07,629
but my wife loves seafood.

2017
01:16:07,696 --> 01:16:09,364
I didn't use to drink coffee.

2018
01:16:09,431 --> 01:16:10,933
I adjusted to her palate.

2019
01:16:10,999 --> 01:16:11,900
OH MY

2020
01:16:11,967 --> 01:16:13,435
The lover boy in the world of baseball.

2021
01:16:13,502 --> 01:16:14,603
THE LOVER BOY TAKES THE PLATE

2022
01:16:14,670 --> 01:16:16,505
The final gateway before the championship.

2023
01:16:16,572 --> 01:16:18,006
This is your last showdown.

2024
01:16:18,073 --> 01:16:19,875
He's throwing salt everywhere!

2025
01:16:19,942 --> 01:16:21,143
He has terrible control.

2026
01:16:21,209 --> 01:16:22,477
BUT HIS SENSE OF HUMOR HITS HOME

2027
01:16:22,544 --> 01:16:23,612
He could always do that!

2028
01:16:23,679 --> 01:16:24,980
Sam was a genius too.

2029
01:16:25,047 --> 01:16:26,248
You should've done it long ago.

2030
01:16:26,315 --> 01:16:27,349
He finally came to his senses.

2031
01:16:27,416 --> 01:16:28,984
Are you rooting for me or bashing me?

2032
01:16:29,051 --> 01:16:30,052
WHAT HAPPENED TO CHEF SAINT?

2033
01:16:30,118 --> 01:16:32,287
Their fate will be decided now.

2034
01:16:32,354 --> 01:16:33,589
He makes cuts on the squid.

2035
01:16:33,655 --> 01:16:35,624
-And he fights back by cutting too.
-My gosh!

2036
01:16:35,691 --> 01:16:37,859
-He's determined to win.
-How will he beat that?

2037
01:16:37,926 --> 01:16:39,494
The last round of the regular league.

2038
01:16:39,561 --> 01:16:41,830
-Oh, no.
-Who's the winner?

2039
01:16:44,533 --> 01:16:46,234
I thought nothing would make my life hard

2040
01:16:46,301 --> 01:16:47,603
once I retired.

2041
01:16:59,214 --> 01:17:04,219
Subtitle translation by: Eunsook Youn
